class T13Types
{

    public static $post_type;
    public static $menus = array();
    public static $ids;
    public static $T13Elementals = array(
        array(
            'Type' => 'Boon',
            'Description' => 'A Boon is a simple integer that represents how powerful something is in T13. Boons are an open-ended number scheme with number values similar is size to the statistics and characteristics of other roleplaying games.',
            'Rules' => 'Boons must be associated with a Facet, as they are essential related to Facet Sway. Boons can be created from Reducing a Value. Boons are considered a type of Thread.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Value',
            'Description' => 'A Value is a simple integer that represents an approximate real world value for a Facet Boon.',
            'Rules' => 'Value can be calculated from Boons, or suggested by real world values such as weight in Kilograms, height in inches (technically this varies with the actual size being between &times;2.4 and &times;2.6 in cm, depending upon nutritional factors, but close to an inch), etc. Values of Boons may be added to find the Value of the combined Boon. '
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Super-Value',
            'Description' => 'Super-Value is to a Value as a Value is to a Boon. They are rarely used except when exceptionally powerful events are occurring, or Superpowered Characters like demi-gods and aliens are involved.',
            'Rules' => 'Super Value can be calculated from Value as Value is calculated from Boon.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Score',
            'Description' => 'A Score is a simple integer that is created by a Facet Boon performing an average amount of work to create a Score. Scores can also be created by rolling Dice.',
            'Rules' => 'Scores are usually created by Facet Sway, but are often measured in Tao Sway or Chi/Pips for simplicity. A Score is calculated from a Boon the same way as a Boon is calculated from a Value, we call this Reducing the Boon.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Boon Die',
            'Description' => 'Each Boon has an associated Die that it can roll to generate a Score in Tao or Facet Sway.',
            'Rules' => 'The average roll of this Boon die will always equal the Score of the Boon.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Facet',
            'Description' => 'Facets are the components of reality. Everything in existence has some connection to at least one of the Facets. Most Characters are made from a mixture of all them.',
            'Rules' => 'Facets divide the Omniverse into 24 components. Each Facet has an Anti-Facet that it is directly associated with, and is considered that Facet’s opposite'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Proficiency',
            'Description' => 'A Proficiency is a quanta of information. Everything known about a subject can be summed up in a Proficiency, for example, a Muscles Proficiency may allow someone to be muscle as well as use muscles, it may even let them know the chemical secrets of muscles (if they also have Chemicals and Secrets Proficiencies too)',
            'Rules' => 'Proficiencies are a Thread. They consist of a name the Thread is known by in the system, as well as any aliases it may have in-universe. Proficiencies should include a description, that helps define the limits of the Proficiency, but these may be missing for some Proficiencies, this usually indicates that strict limits should be placed upon the Proficiency’s use until it has been better defined.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Hitch',
            'Description' => 'A Hitch is a Knot that acts on Characters as a limiting factor to their power and as a response to things that happen in the narrative. Hitches are the self-imposed trials, the socially-imposed responsibilities, the wild roll of dice that is the genetic lottery, or the curse of a frog prince. A Hitch may represent a Phobia, an Allergy, a lost love, having your parents murdered in a back alley, you know formative moments and character problems that must be overcome.',
            'Rules' => 'Hitches are Facet based Knots that combines Proficiency Threads, that defines the Hitch Type, the Gnarls of the Hitch, and the Triggers, that define how the hitch behaves, as well as a Hitch Boon that defines how bad the Hitch is.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Annex',
            'Description' => 'An Annex is a knot of Proficiencies and at least one Boon that work together, becoming something new. Annexes can represent Skills a Character has acquired, Talents that have been developed, or Powers that have emerged.',
            'Rules' => 'Proficiencies are combined together to form Annexes. 2 Profs make a Skill, more than that and you are creating a Talent or a Power. Proficiencies may add Facet Values from a Character to create larger Values that calculate the Boon for the Annex. Annexes generate Sway and Scores as their Channelling Facet usually, but they can also generate the Sway of the Annex Root as well. Talent and Power Annexes usually have a Tangle as well as Umbral and Nimbed Proficiencies, which all alter how the Annex may be used and works.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Character',
            'Description' => 'Characters are people, or something close to it anyway, depending upon your definition of people. Characters are notable in T13 for their Names which effect how they gain Yin and Yang. Even the most basic T13 Character should have a unique name. There are several types of Character each with their own complexity and level of balance in the game.',
            'Rules' => 'Characters generally consist of a complete selection of Boons, a bunch of Proficiencies, a handful of Hitches, a few Skills, a few of Talents and perhaps one or two powers. More powerful Characters will tend to have bigger and more of everything.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Descendant',
            'Description' => 'A Descendant is almost everything that isn’t a Character. Descendants come in a number of types, some of which you will be familiar with, such as Tools, Equipment, Armour, Weapons, others are equally familiar but not generally thought the same, such as Education, Hobbies, Books read, as well as buildings, rooms, and other Locations.',
            'Rules' => 'Descendants are a collection of Annexes created by a Character using their own Boons, but that has a separate existence, like say a sword, perhaps built around a "Cutting Blade" Skill.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Sway Cache',
            'Description' => 'Sway Caches are resources, too large to be easily created, but not important enough to warrant a Descendant being made. They include things like "Briefcase of Cash", "Food for weeks" and "Plenty of air in here" and can represent the success of any Facet’s Action.',
            'Rules' => 'Sway Cache is a knot of a Proficiency that defines the resource, and a Score.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => '',
            'Description' => '',
            'Rules' => ''
        ) 
    );
	 public static $pactAnnexes = array(
	 array(
		  'Type' => 'Group',
		  'Description' => 'A Group is a loose group of Characters who freely associate, but are not held together by anything other than friendship or economic interests.',
		  'Rules' => 'Groups have only a Pact (Size) Annex, but never have Sub-Annexes although they can have Proficiencies with a number of Extra Slots equal to the Pact Score.'
	 ) ,
		array(
		  'Type' => 'Club',
		  'Description' => 'A Club is a non-professional association, that typically has a smaller membership (although some clubs can rise to national sizes this is unusual), and is focused around a particular interest, hobby or skill.',
		  'Rules' => 'Club Pacts are smaller groups with at least one Sub-Skill Annex. Clubs may grant members grant access to the Skills and select Proficiencies.'
		) ,
		array(
			 'Type' => 'Guild',
			 'Description' => 'Guild Pacts indicates a larger society — usually a professional, trade organization or corporation.',
			 'Rules' => 'Guild Pacts can support Sub-Talents, Sub-Skills and Extra Proficiencies.'
		) ,
		array(
			 'Type' => 'Society',
			 'Description' => 'Society Pacts represents large numbers of normal people, or smaller groups of powerful people, working towards common goals. Often Secret Societies, large corporations, and most towns or cities will fall in this tier of Pact.',
			 'Rules' => 'A Society Pact has Powers, Talents, Skills and Proficiencies that it makes available to members.'
		) ,
		array(
			 'Type' => 'Nation',
			 'Description' => 'Nation Pacts are huge cultural and economic Pacts, that can mean hundreds of thousands, or even millions of people who share some identity.',
			 'Rules' => 'Nations have a Super-Annex as well as Powers, Talents, Skills and Proficiencies.'
		) ,
		array(
			 'Type' => 'Trusts',
			 'Description' => 'Trusts are often small business partnerships, or any committed relationships where all partners are fully invested and trust each other.',
			 'Rules' => 'Trusts have Sway invested in them, much as a Trophy Descendant does, representing the Trust between all members as they each sacrifice something to the Pact beyond mere membership. This sacrifice (whatever it is and they vary immensely between Trust Pacts) will grant these Trusted members an Edge. Note that a Trust Pact may have both Trusted Members and Untrusted Members (who do not gain Edges).'
		) ,
		array(
			 'Type' => 'Leagues',
			 'Description' => 'Leagues are often large organisations, often with political or philanthropic goals. Smaller Leagues are possible, if members include Heroes.',
			 'Rules' => 'League Pacts have additional Chi stored in them, usually by Hero level Characters. League Members are granted additional Edges by the Pact. Note a League Pact may have League, Trust and common (untrusted) members.'
		) ,
		array(
			 'Type' => 'Covenants',
			 'Description' => 'Covenants are powerful, and often mystical or magical organisations of exceptionally powerful people. A Guild of Archmages for example, or a nation that included supernatural creatures in its populace.',
			 'Rules' => 'Covenant Pacts have additional Yarn stored in them by powerful Characters like Yarn-Tellers. Covenants are often supernatural Pacts, and grant the members all manner of Edges and Glows. It is possible that a Covenant may have League, Trust or Common (untrusted) members as well, but this is less likely.'
		) ,
		array(
			 'Type' => 'Possession',
			 'Description' => 'Possession Pacts are created by supernatural entities, such as spirits, gods and the Increated, possessing other, usually more physical Characters (or Descendants). Possession Pacts can be voluntary, where a Character elects to let another possess them, or involuntary possessions, where the Character has less say and may be trying to fight the possession.',
			 'Rules' => 'Possession Pacts vary by the level of control that the possessing Character can produce, and are usually created with Twists (although Sway and Chi possessions are possible too for less Demonic possessions).'
		) ,

	 );
	 public static $pactMemberships = array(
		 array(
			  'Type' => 'Belonging',
			  'Description' => 'Belonging membership is the most common membership of any Pact. It is the most basic membership that it is possible to have.',
			  'Rules' => 'Belonging Membership cannot grant Sub-Annexes but does grant the member access to at least 1 Proficiency from the Pact.'
		 ) ,
		 array(
			  'Type' => 'Hobbyist',
			  'Description' => 'Hobbyist Membership represents the highest membership that a Character can reach in a Pact without some sort of professional, or blood-line based, patronage.',
			  'Rules' => 'Hobbyist Membership grants the Member access to a single Sub-Skill from the Pact, and a number of Proficiencies.'
		 ) ,
		 array(
			  'Type' => 'Paid',
			  'Description' => 'Paid Membership represents the minimum level of membership for professionals within the Pact. If you are an employee of a company for example, then you will have Paid Membership, as would a fully paid up member of a trade union or similar guild.',
			  'Rules' => 'Paid Membership in a Pact grants the member a Sub-Talent, some Sub-Skills, and Proficiencies. Costs are indicated by Talent Umbrals and Hitches.'
		 ) ,
		 array(
			  'Type' => 'Executive',
			  'Description' => 'Executive Membership represents a powerful type of membership, influential within the Pact, such as middle management.',
			  'Rules' => 'Executive Membership grants a Character access to a single Sub-Power, as well as Sub-Talents, Sub-Skills and Proficiencies from the Pact.'
		 ) ,
		 array(
			  'Type' => 'Courtier',
			  'Description' => 'Courtier Membership represents the highest tier of membership that most members can ever hope to attain. Courtiers are very powerful, and influential, often holding senior management positions within the Pact.',
			  'Rules' => 'Courtier Membership grants the member access to the Super-Annex of the Pact as a Super-Skill, as well as a selection of Sub-Powers, Sub-Talents, Sub-Skills and Proficiencies.'
		 ) ,
		 array(
			  'Type' => 'Sovereign',
			  'Description' => 'Sovereign Membership is the highest level of membership that is ever available to a Pact Member. The Sovereign is the absolute leader of the Pact (there can be up to 3 Sovereigns in some Pacts, but most have a singular Sovereign). In a possession pact the Sovereign has control of the physical body equal to their control of the Psychosocial Space.',
			  'Rules' => 'Sovereigns gain access to the full version of the Super-Annex of the Pact, as well as all Sub-Powers, Sub-Talents, Sub-Skills and Proficiencies the Pact may have. How the Sovereign is chosen can vary greatly from Pact to Pact, and may involve some Quest, Test or Ordeal to decide the Sovereign. Possession Pacts for example decide the Sovereign based on a Psychosocial Ordeal, to secure and control the Character’s Psychosocial Space.'
		 ) ,
	 );
    
     public static $annexNimbedSlots = array (
        array('Type'=>'Banal Game / Setting / Character', 'Talent_Nimbeds'=>'Each Umbral interacting with the Tangle opens 1 Nimbed Slot. i.e. 1 Umbral allows 1 Nimbed','Power_Nimbeds'=>'Each Umbral interacting with the Tangle opens 2 Nimbed Slots. i.e. 2 Umbrals allows 4 Nimbeds'),
        array('Type'=>'Intrepid Game / Setting / Character', 'Talent_Nimbeds'=>'Each Umbral interacting with the Tangle opens 2 Nimbed Slot. i.e. 1 Umbral allows 2 Nimbeds','Power_Nimbeds'=>'The total number Umbrals interacting with the Tangle treated as a Boon, opens a number of Nimbed Slots equal to the Value. i.e. 2 Umbrals allows 5 Nimbeds.'),
        array('Type'=>'Bold Game / Setting / Character', 'Talent_Nimbeds'=>'The total number Umbrals interacting with the Tangle treated as a Boon, opens a number of Nimbed Slots equal to the Value. e.g. 2 Umbrals allows 5 Nimbeds.','Power_Nimbeds'=>'The total number of Umbrals and Tangles that are interacting, treated as a Boon opens a number of Nimbed Slots equal to the Value. e.g. 1 Umbral and 1 Tangle allows 5 Nimbeds.'),
     );
     public static $monsterFacetRules = array(
        array('Type'=>'Banal','Description'=>'Banal Monsters are just humans who are temperamentally monstrous. The Banal Werewolf may believe they are wolf, but they are just some poor deluded soul howling at the moon. Typically such Monsters are due to Genre and Setting Limitations.','Rules'=>'Monster Facets are increased in Boon by the total number of Monster Facets available, as though it were a Scale effect. So a Boon 13 Monster (II) would be Boon 15 and add 83 Value to any annex instead of 66.'),
        array('Type'=>'Intrepid','Description'=>'Intrepid Monsters are mostly humans who are a little monstrous, although you might encounter the occasional monstrous animal, alien or robot. Intrepid Monsters are often described with animalistic features, such as yellow or reflective eyes, sharp teeth, claws, etc even when they are humans. The Intrepid werewolf may have long pointed nails, sharp canines and wild eyes, but they still look human.','Rules'=>'Monster Facets add the number of Monster Facets to the Boon but also adds the original Value. A Boon 13 Monster (II) Facet gives 83+66=149 or Boon 22 (ish).'),
        array('Type'=>'Bold','Description'=>'Bold Monsters are pretty monstrous, often having clear signs they are not normal. The Bold werewolf actually becomes a wolf-man, perhaps even having a short snout and fur. Bold monsters are common in fantasy, and can be aliens or robots in science-fiction.','Rules'=>'All Monster Facet Values are multiplied by 1 + the number of Monster Facets. So a Boon 13 Monster (II) Facet would have a Value of 198, making it the equivalent of Boon 25 or 26.'),
        array('Type'=>'Monstrous','Description'=>'Monstrous Monsters are true monsters. These are the werewolves that have wolf heads, dog legs, are only injured by silver, and tend to be about eight feet tall. Such Monsters are common to Horror Settings and some Fantasy settings.','Rules'=>'Monstrous Monster Facets increase the Boon by the current number of Monster Facets, then take the Value as a Boon and halve. So a Monster (II) Boon 13 becomes 15 with so 83 &divide; 2 that becomes Boon 41 adding 448 Value to any Annex.'),
        array('Type'=>'Twisted','Description'=>'Twisted Monsters are the worst Monsters, usually fused with the forces of the Increated, although science, aliens and cosmic forces can also twist a Monster.','Rules'=>'Twisted Monster Facets increase the Boon by multiplying the Boon by 1 + Number of Monster Facets + Stored Twists. So Boon 13 Monster(II) with 1 Twists gives 13 &times; 4 = Boon 52.'),
     );
     public static $monsterRules = array(
        array('Type'=>'Banal','Description'=>'Banal Monsters are just humans who are temperamentally monstrous. The Banal Werewolf may believe they are wolf, but they are just some poor deluded soul howling at the moon. Typically such Monsters are due to Genre and Setting Limitations.','Monster_Facet_Rules'=>'Monster Facets are increased in Boon by the total number of Monster Facets available, as though it were a Scale effect. So a Boon 13 Monster (II) would be Boon 15 and add 83 Value to any annex instead of 66.','Monster_Pool_Rules'=>'Banal Monsters are very limited in their Monster Pool abilities. Banal Monster Pool Bonuses may only add the Monster Pool Size Score (the Number of Cards currently in the Pool Reduced) to the Monster’s Actions. They may only use one Monster Pool Bonus at a time.','Monster_Pool_Draw'=>'1 card only from 1 Monster Facet','Monster_Pool_Limit'=>'Highest Monster Facet Score','Monster_Pool_Initial'=>'Banal Monsters begin with 2 cards in their Monster Pool, unless specified by Monster Facet.'),
        array('Type'=>'Intrepid','Description'=>'Intrepid Monsters are mostly humans who are a little monstrous, although you might encounter the occasional monstrous animal, alien or robot. Intrepid Monsters are often described with animalistic features, such as yellow or reflective eyes, sharp teeth, claws, etc even when they are humans. The Intrepid werewolf may have long pointed nails, sharp canines and wild eyes, but they still look human.','Monster_Facet_Rules'=>'Monster Facets add the number of Monster Facets to the Boon but also adds the original Value. A Boon 13 Monster (II) Facet gives 83+66=149 or Boon 22.','Monster_Pool_Rules'=>'Intrepid Monsters have a strong connection to their Monster Pool and can use it more easily. Intrepid Monster Pool Bonuses may add Monster Pool Size Score (Number of cards Reduced) to any dice Score or card Pips on the Monster’s Actions.','Monster_Pool_Draw'=>'The appropriate Monster Facet Draw', 'Monster_Pool_Limit'=>'Monster Annex Score','Monster_Pool_Initial'=>'Intrepid Monsters begin with a number of cards equal to their lowest Monster Facet Score.'),
        array('Type'=>'Bold','Description'=>'Bold Monsters are pretty monstrous, often having clear signs they are not normal. The Bold werewolf actually becomes a wolf-man, perhaps even having a short snout and fur. Bold monsters are common in fantasy, and can be aliens or robots in science-fiction.','Monster_Facet_Rules'=>'All Monster Facet Values are multiplied by 1 + the number of Monster Facets. So a Boon 13 Monster (II) Facet would have a Value of 198, making it the equivalent of Boon 26.','Monster_Pool_Rules'=>'Bold Monsters have a robust connection with their Monster Pool. Bold Monster Pool Bonuses allow the Monster to add Monster Pool Size (the number of cards) to any Dice Score or card Pips of any suitable Monster Action. They may Draw cards to the Monster Pool from any Monster Facet when applicable.','Monster_Pool_Draw'=>'The appropriate Monster Facet Draw +1 per Monster Facet', 'Monster_Pool_Limit'=>'Lowest Monster Facet Boon','Monster_Pool_Initial'=>'Bold Monsters begin with a number of cards equal to their Highest Monster Facet Score'),
        array('Type'=>'Monstrous','Description'=>'Monstrous Monsters are true monsters. These are the werewolves that have wolf heads, dog legs, are only injured by silver, and tend to be about eight feet tall. Such Monsters are common to Horror Settings and some Fantasy settings.','Monster_Facet_Rules'=>'Monstrous Monster Facets increase the Boon by the current number of Monster Facets, then take the Value as a Boon and halve. So a Monster (II) Boon 13 becomes 15 with so 83 &divide; 2 that becomes Boon 41 adding 448 Value to any Annex.','Monster_Pool_Rules'=>'Monstrous Monsters have an excellent connection with their Monster Pool. Their Bonuses may add Monster Pool Size (Number of cards) Success Levels to any appropriate Monster Action. They may Draw cards to their Monster Pool from any Monster Facet, whenever appropriate.','Monster_Pool_Draw'=>'Monster Facet Score', 'Monster_Pool_Limit'=>'Highest Monster Facet Boon','Monster_Pool_Initial'=>'Monstrous Monsters begin with a number of cards equal to their Highest Monster Facet Score'),
        array('Type'=>'Twisted','Description'=>'Twisted Monsters are the worst Monsters, usually fused with the forces of the Increated, although science, aliens and cosmic forces can also twist a Monster.','Monster_Facet_Rules'=>'Twisted Monster Facets increase the Boon by multiplying the Boon by 1 + Number of Monster Facets + Stored Twists. So Boon 13 Monster(II) with 1 Twists gives 13 &times; 4 = Boon 52.','Monster_Pool_Rules'=>'Twisted Monsters have a strong connection with Monster Facets and Pools. Their Bonuses may add Monster Pool Size (Number of cards) Success Levels to any appropriate Monster Action. They may Draw cards to their Monster Pool from any Monster Facet, whenever appropriate.','Monster_Pool_Draw'=>'Monster Facet Score +1 per Monster Facet', 'Monster_Pool_Limit'=>'Monster Annex Boon','Monster_Pool_Initial'=>'Twisted Monsters begin with a number of cards equal to their Monster Facet Score'),
     );

    public static $successAndFailureLevels = array(
   	array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Cards', 'Type'=>'Lost Opportunity', 'Description'=>'Sometimes a failure can close a window of opportunity that was previously open to us.', 'Rules'=>'Character must Discard one Card from their Ordeal Pool.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Cards', 'Type'=>'Limit Divergence', 'Description'=>'Sometimes a failure when you are trying to pull your punches, or mitigate a blow, will cause you to do more damage. Conversely, sometimes you swing for fences, but get only a glancing blow.', 'Rules'=>'A current Attack’s Wound Limit is altered one step up or down by the Failure (usually down unless the Wound is on the Character or they are trying to capture the target alive).'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Combat', 'Type'=>'Wide Open', 'Description'=>'Sometimes a small mistake in how you stand or move can grant your opponent an opening.', 'Rules'=>'When the Character is next Attacked, 1 card will be made Unsoakable.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Communication', 'Type'=>'Mumbled', 'Description'=>'Sometimes when you are communicating a single word or phrase can be mumbled and not understood.', 'Rules'=>'Typically a single word (or short phrase) is "deleted" from the communication, a sound is heard there, but not understood as any word.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Complexity', 'Type'=>'Mistargeted', 'Description'=>'Large complex machines and systems can be very complex to use. Sometimes a small user fault can create a situation where a complex system ends up doing whatever it does on the wrong person.', 'Rules'=>'Typically the system or machine will target the wrong Character initially. This is usually randomly determined.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Descendant', 'Type'=>'Drop', 'Description'=>'Try as you might to use a Descendant, sometimes they just slip through your fingers.', 'Rules'=>'At the end of the Action, regardless of the rest of the result the Descendant being used currently is dropped. Recovering the Dropped item is usually a single action.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Dramatic', 'Type'=>'Blunder', 'Description'=>'A blunder is a dramatic failure that is caused by a Character acting as though they could not see or do not understand what was going on. Such blunders can include a Character thinking they are on a different side to the one they are on.', 'Rules'=>'For NPCs a blunder is usually a mistake but for PCs, rather than causing a Player to look foolish, or stupid and destroying Player agency, Blunders reveal a Turn in the Plot. Causing a Character to change sides or even for the Central Conflict to alter. Dramatic Blunders can be very complicated to improvise, and should not be attempted unless you are experienced at using Turns.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Emotional', 'Type'=>'Upset', 'Description'=>'Sometimes a failure is a minor emotional upset.', 'Rules'=>'Character is affected by a 1 card Negative emotional affect, may also Splash to affect Allies.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Environmental', 'Type'=>'Specific', 'Description'=>'Sometimes some specific aspect of the environment around a Character or the Location they find themselves in causes an error in their actions. These are usually things overlooked, or easily forgotten about the Location, like the ground being slippery, the location being too loud to communicate easily, or space being filled with cobwebs.', 'Rules'=>'Specific Failures have specific consequences that should generally have a cost of up to 9 Chi. Examples include: Pulling and playing an Ordeal card to move the Character in the wrong direction, or injure them; increasing or decreasing Wound Limits on an attack; adding an additional Soak Layer (such as the cobwebs, tight quarters, mists or foliage); or causing damage from an attack to Splash unexpectedly.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Investigation', 'Type'=>'Overlook', 'Description'=>'In an investigation the simplest mistake can be to overlook a piece of evidence and never collect it. ', 'Rules'=>'1 piece of evidence or revelation is completely ignored and effectively discarded by this Character. It may be found later by another Character, if important enough.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Logical', 'Type'=>'Inconsistent', 'Description'=>'An inconsistent logical failure usually occurs when two propositions cannot both be true at the same time. Often these sorts of logical failures occur when lying, a Character may admit to having seen something that they should not have been.', 'Rules'=>'Inconsistent failures add a chance of Disbelief to any action. Disbelief of some part of the Action will not negate the whole action, but it can render that disbelieved part moot.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Narrative', 'Type'=>'Tonal Dissonance', 'Description'=>'Sometimes an action is not strictly a failure, but alters the Tone of the Scene making similar actions harder afterwards. A sniper that shoots a target, regardless of whether he succeeds or fails, is likely to put everyone on the defensive.', 'Rules'=>'The Tone of the Current Scene is altered to match the current Action’s Anti-Facet.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Proficiency', 'Type'=>'Ineffective', 'Description'=>'Sometimes a failure may make a Character question if they even know a subject at all, and perhaps go and refresh their knowledge of a subject.', 'Rules'=>'Character must delete or remove 1 Proficiency as they question their own knowledge on the subject.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Psychosocial', 'Type'=>'Perturbing', 'Description'=>'Sometimes a failure will effect the impression that others have of you negatively.', 'Rules'=>'Reduces the Impression that the Character has of you by 1 Social Impression Level.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Score', 'Type'=>'Pathetic', 'Description'=>'Sometimes a failure level can only lower the Score that the Action created. This is the least useful or fun result you can choose. Honestly, it probably shouldn’t even exist as an option, but occasionally it is the only Failure that makes sense.', 'Rules'=>'A single Failure Level will lower the rolled Score by 32 Banal Tao Sway (-8 Pips/Chi).'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Stress', 'Type'=>'Stressful', 'Description'=>'Any amount of failure in any situation can always be stressful.', 'Rules'=>'The Character Gains Stress, this is can be upto 9 Stress, but should never fill a Character with Stress (and can be as low as 1 Stress or a normal Stress Gain).'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Stress', 'Type'=>'Strained', 'Description'=>'A failure when doing something physical can result in a strained muscle, but you can also strain your mind, heart and soul.', 'Rules'=>'The Character Gains Strains on the Annex or Facet Die that is being rolled for the Action. This Failure can add upto 3 Strains to a single Die, but not to the Stress-Strain Limit.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Stress', 'Type'=>'Shocked', 'Description'=>'A failure can be a shocking event, causing a Character to hesitate, freeze, or even collapse. Sometimes failure can even be traumatic.', 'Rules'=>'The Character Annex or Facet Die rolled is now Shocked. This is often regardless of Stress or Strains.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Sway', 'Type'=>'Loss', 'Description'=>'When a Character is generating and accumulating Sway for any purpose they may sometimes lose some of that value along the way due to minor failures.', 'Rules'=>'A single failure level will cost Sway equivalent to the Character’s normal Sway Gain (and up to 9 Chi equivalent at maximum).'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Transformation', 'Type'=>'Blemish', 'Description'=>'When a desired transformation goes a little bit wrong we get an undesired, disfiguring blemish. Some part of the surface that is the wrong colour or texture.', 'Rules'=>'A Blemish will reduce the value of a Descendant by &frac13;, such that a Descendant normally costing 30 Chi will only be worth 20 Chi if Blemished. '),
		array('Level'=>'1 Failure', 'Category'=>'Wellness', 'Type'=>'Injury', 'Description'=>'Failure when performing any physical task can result in a pulled muscle, and with perfect timing a pulled muscle could distract you, cause you to fall, hit your head badly, and even die.', 'Rules'=>'The Character is attacked by a 1 Ordeal Card Attack at the current Stakes. This Attack may be soaked as usual.'),

		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Cards', 'Type'=>'Extra Effort', 'Description'=>'Success can make a Character try harder than ever before, even more than some thought possible.', 'Rules'=>'Play an additional 1 Ordeal Card from your Ordeal Pool on the current Action.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Cards', 'Type'=>'Limit Divergence', 'Description'=>'Success when you are trying to hurt someone can mean you have targeted some weak spot, or internal organ. Or perhaps if you were on the receiving end of a punch, you might want to reduce its power somehow.', 'Rules'=>'The Wound Limit of the current Attack the Character is making or taking can be raised or lowered by one. So a Maiming Wound could be reduced to a Flesh or potentially increased to Crippling. Note that this does not alter the Pips required at the current Stakes.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Cards', 'Type'=>'More Choice', 'Description'=>'Success can offer a Character more choices, opportunities and chances.', 'Rules'=>'Draw an additional 1 Ordeal Card to your Ordeal Pool.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Combat', 'Type'=>'Create Opening', 'Description'=>'Success in combat can allow a Character to create an opening in their opponent’s defence, even momentarily.', 'Rules'=>'The Character may make one card of their attack Unsoakable.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Combat', 'Type'=>'Deadliness', 'Description'=>'Success in combat can allow a Character to alter how deadly their attack is, or how deadly the hit they took was.', 'Rules'=>'The Character may Alter the Wound Limit card a level on the Attack they are making or an incoming attack.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Combat', 'Type'=>'Fend Off', 'Description'=>'Success in combat can allow a Character to fend off the worst of an Attack.', 'Rules'=>'The Character may Discard one card from an incoming attack.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Communication', 'Type'=>'Expressive', 'Description'=>'Success in communication can allow you to communicate more than just a single piece of information. It is possible to even communicate one innocuous message to one person and a secret message along side it to a friend, ally or co-conspirator. Expressive communication can also have psychosocial effects or create emotional responses.', 'Rules'=>'Expressive Communication can either <ul><li>Hide a piece of information being communicated from some of those listening (Spot: Concealed)</li><li>Move a Character listening in a Psychosocial Space (increase or decrease impression for example)</li><li>Create a 1 card Psych effect in those hearing the communication.</li></ul>'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Complexity', 'Type'=>'Subtle', 'Description'=>'Success when using complex systems or devices can be a subtle effect. Simply making it harder to trace back through the system. If five people are fighting in the dark, does anyone know who swung the first punch?', 'Rules'=>'The effects of the Action are Obscured and Secured by the Complexity of the system or machine or have become more difficult to trace back to the Character. This is the equivalent of Spot Obscured to even detect something is wrong, Spot Secured to actually unravel the system.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Descendant', 'Type'=>'Impediment', 'Description'=>'A Descendant can often be used to create an Obstacle for another Character, at least with a Successful use. A gunshot for example can start a stampede, drop a security gate, or set off fire suppression systems.', 'Rules'=>'From the Ordeal Cards of the current Action one may be used to create a suitable 1 card Obstacle for anyone following the Character.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Dramatic', 'Type'=>'Managed Expectation', 'Description'=>'Success can mean a lot of things, especially in a dramatic situation, with a climbing Drama Pool and sense of impending incidents. Success here means lowering that drama before it strikes.', 'Rules'=>'The Character can remove one die from the Drama Pool. It is usual to remove the die with the lowest number of faces. Yarn-Tellers may reroll the Pool after (which may create Drama), but this costs 1 Yarn.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Emotional', 'Type'=>'Emotive', 'Description'=>'Emotional success can stir emotions in others, making them laugh, fume, or cry.', 'Rules'=>'The Character may play a 1 Card Psych effect upon another Character (or Characters). This will typically be a positive emotion if played on a friend or ally, and a negative emotion if played upon an enemy or opposition, but the choice is the Player’s.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Environmental', 'Type'=>'Situational', 'Description'=>'Sometimes a Success means spotting something in the environment and using it to your advantage. This can lead to swinging across rooms, dominoing book cases, dropping chandeliers, or broken glass on people, or realising the hacker’s computer is plugged into your systems next to you.', 'Rules'=>'Situational Successes can typically add some additional benefit for the Character based upon the Location and what it contains. This benefit may have a cost up to 9 Chi, which could allow a Character to alter their appearance completely, or move them 9 Pips closer to their target, add an Obstacle, keep themselves hidden, etc. '),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Investigation', 'Type'=>'Discovery', 'Description'=>'A Success during an investigation can mean you have made a Discovery. A Discovery is often not quite a Clue, but might point us towards where a real CLue may be found.', 'Rules'=>'Discoveries are pieces of information, that while not Clues in their own right, are revelatory in nature. They often lead a Character to an Location where a Clue might be found, or to Character who knows something useful, but not essential. Discoveries are at best supporting evidence, but are never important enough to build a case on.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Logical', 'Type'=>'Validity', 'Description'=>'Sometimes Success can make something sound correct, regardless of whether it really is. Logic and reason can build cases for almost any action, and it can be hard to use moral or ethical objections on a well constructed logical arguments. Logical Validity is its own form of truth, and for some Characters the only truth they will believe.', 'Rules'=>'Characters that hear the argument or see the Action believe it to be true. This means they must actively disbelieve this "truth" before they can undo its effects.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Narrative', 'Type'=>'Tonal Resonance', 'Description'=>'After a Narrative Success the whole tone of a situation can change, as perhaps a Sniper shoots someone and everything becomes combative.', 'Rules'=>'The Tonal Resonance Success sets the Tone of the Current Scene to the Facet of this Action. The Tone may later return (especially if there is a Tone Embodiment), but this will usually require another Tonal Resonance Success (or a Dissonant Failure).'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Proficiency', 'Type'=>'Breakthrough', 'Description'=>'A great success when using Proficiencies can result in a Breakthrough. These Successes can teach a Character new information, or allow them to combine their knowledge in new ways.', 'Rules'=>'Breakthrough Successes allow Characters to either combine the Proficiencies they just rolled into an Annex (often a new Skill), as though they had rolled a Proficiency Crisis, or to learn new Proficiencies. Breakthrough Successes are often used earlier in the game as Characters are pushed to learn new abilities by Mentors.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Psychosocial', 'Type'=>'Popular', 'Description'=>'Sometimes Success can mean a Character becomes more well liked and popular. Of course, such popularity is often short-lived and may become notoriety in time, but for now people should think well of them.', 'Rules'=>'Move the Target Psychosocially (the equivalent of 9 Pips). For example, a Popular Success could increase or decrease the Target’s Impression of the Character one Social Ordeal level.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Score', 'Type'=>'High-score', 'Description'=>'If all you are doing is generating Score then Success just means more Score.', 'Rules'=>'High-score Success adds 32 Banal Tao Sway (+8 Pips) to the Score'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Stress', 'Type'=>'Relief', 'Description'=>'Sometimes a small win is all we need to relieve the stress, strain or shocks we have been feeling.', 'Rules'=>'A Relief Success Level can Relieve upto 9 Stress, 3 Strains or 1 Shock at a time, technically it can Relieve 1 Shock, 1 Strain and 2 Stress at the same time.'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Sway', 'Type'=>'Gain', 'Description'=>'Sometimes Success means a little something extra for you, be it extra Health, Wealth or whatever.', 'Rules'=>'A Gain Success causes the Character to Gain Sway equal to their normal Gain (and no more than 9 Chi equivalent Maximum).'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Transformation', 'Type'=>'Functional', 'Description'=>'Sometimes the best we can hope for when converting something between forms, is that the thing actually works in its new form.', 'Rules'=>'Functional Successes can be used to provide access to suitable Annex Slots in the new form. Upto 4 Skill Slots, 1 Talent and 2 Skill Slots, or 1 Power and 1 Skill Slot can be unlocked with a single Functional Success. If these Annexes are from the original form then they may be used as normal, Annexes specific to the new form will have to paid for (Annex Boon + Proficiencies)'),
		array('Level'=>'1 Success', 'Category'=>'Wellness', 'Type'=>'Healing Surge', 'Description'=>'Sometimes Success means you are able to shrug off lesser wounds, as though they never happened.', 'Rules'=>'A Healing Surge Success can completely heal and remove 1 Flesh Wound and 1 Distract or 4 Distract Wounds instantly.'),

		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Cards', 'Type'=>'Doomed', 'Description'=>'Failures can mean destiny has other plans for you.', 'Rules'=>'The Yarn-Teller should Pull and Play a Wyrd Tarot Card upon the Failing Character. The Card should be played in the least useful way on the Character.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Cards', 'Type'=>'Forgotten Dream', 'Description'=>'Failures can affect your unconscious mind, snatching away futures you once considered possible.', 'Rules'=>'Forgotten Dream Failures make a Character Discard 1 Wyrd Tarot Card from their Hand.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Cards', 'Type'=>'Sucker Punched', 'Description'=>'Failures can combine and the moment you let your guard down, you get hurt again.', 'Rules'=>'Sucker Punch Failures allow an opponent to immediately Draw 3 Cards into their Pool and then immediately play 2 Cards from their Pool, usually as an Attack on the Character.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Combat', 'Type'=>'Enemy Reserves', 'Description'=>'Failures during combat can mean that the enemy gets some reinforcements.', 'Rules'=>'The enemy can Summon additional troops (this may be magical, telepathic, technological, pre-arranged, called, whistled, etc.), typically this is one Demon, Goblin, Hero, or Force-of-Nature Extra; or two Grunts or Cast Extras; or 3 Chorus Extras; or upto 9 Vexes. This should be balanced against the ability and power level of the Character, and may include a Monster (I).'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Communication', 'Type'=>'Miscommunication', 'Description'=>'Failures in communication can compound making a Character believe you said the exact opposite of what you thought you were saying.', 'Rules'=>'The exact nature of the message you were trying to convey is inverted or reversed, and understood as the opposite. Sometimes a miscommunication will not be a complete inversion of the message, but only if there is some contextual way the message can be interpreted that is actually worse than a complete reversal of intent.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Complexity', 'Type'=>'Misapplication', 'Description'=>'Complex systems have a chaotic nature and that sometimes means you can’t know what to expect. Sure that teleporter device can move you through space, but did you know that one small mistake and it could send you through time, clone you, gene-splice you with a fly, teleport you to a Dark mirror dimension, or you could arrive inside out?', 'Rules'=>'Whatever the normal effect of the system or machine is changed on this application and target. For example if the system is a complex weapon, then rather than attacking them in this instance it may heal or defend the target.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Descendant', 'Type'=>'Jeopardise', 'Description'=>'You know what’s worse than dropping a weapon on the floor? Missing the floor and watching it fall into darkness, or hitting the floor an breaking? Either of them is worse.', 'Rules'=>'The Character must either Draw and Play one Unsoakable Card on the Descendant, or Discard it "Permanently", which actually means they will have to purchase it back (as though it were one more commonality higher than normal, up to Ubiquitous) if they want to find it again.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Dramatic', 'Type'=>'Dramatic Hurdle', 'Description'=>'Sometimes failures can create Hurdles in the Character’s way, complicating the Narrative they are Embodied within.', 'Rules'=>'Dramatic Hurdle Failures create a Facet Hurdle that the Character must face during the Scene.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Emotional', 'Type'=>'Disquieted', 'Description'=>'Sometimes failures create strong emotions for the Character who failed, or those observing them.', 'Rules'=>'The Character will suffer a 2 Card Negative Psych Effect, or an opposed Character will take a 2 Card Positive Psych Effect. '),
		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Environmental', 'Type'=>'Obstacle', 'Description'=>'Failures can compound and create an Obstacle that gets in everyone’s way.', 'Rules'=>'Creates a 2 Card Obstacle in the current Stage or Scene.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Investigation', 'Type'=>'Spoilation', 'Description'=>'Sometimes a Character can make so many failures in an investigation that they end up destroying evidence accidentally.', 'Rules'=>'Spoilation Failures can alter the facts of a case, making some piece of evidence that they have already discovered actually a red herring.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Logical', 'Type'=>'Fallacy', 'Description'=>'Multiple failures of logic usually mean a logical fallacy. Whatever conclusion the Character has come to it is wrong somehow.', 'Rules'=>'Fallacy Failures indicate that the Character has made some mistake in their logic. If they have come to some conclusion then it is incorrect. This can create Red Herrings, mildly ret-con information, and invert already discovered facts.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Narrative', 'Type'=>'Snag', 'Description'=>'Sometimes failures accumulate and create a problem that must be overcome before proceeding.', 'Rules'=>'The Current Scene adds a Snag for the Character’s Side, typically the Snag is selected by the Yarn-Teller from one of the Cards just played in the Character’s Action, or the card atop the Discard Pile.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Proficiency', 'Type'=>'Incompetence', 'Description'=>'Sometimes failures in knowledge can compound, creating a crippling incompetence.', 'Rules'=>'Incompetence Failures cause a Character to take an Unsoakable Crippling Wound, such a Wound should target the largest Annex that was used.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Psychosocial', 'Type'=>'Mindgames', 'Description'=>'Psychosocial Failures can accumulate and create a situation where a Character’s own mindscape begins to turn against them. They may find themselves ambushed by mental Characters that represent their own resentments, previous failures, concerns and worries.', 'Rules'=>'The Character is ambushed within their mindscape Psychosocial Space, with their internal representation Character beset by Internal Characters, such as Archetypes or Monsters from the Id, that represent their fears, concerns and previous failures. Such a situation may create Nightmares or cause expressions of those Archetypes which negatively impact other Character’s '),
		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Score', 'Type'=>'Pitiful', 'Description'=>'When all you are trying to do is amass Score each Failure is going to steal some.', 'Rules'=>'The Action loses 92 Banal Tao Sway Score (-16 Chi/Pips).'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Stress', 'Type'=>'Stressful', 'Description'=>'Compounding Failures are a formula for additional Stress.', 'Rules'=>'The Character Gains 16 Stress rather than their normal Stress Gain.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Sway', 'Type'=>'Costly', 'Description'=>'Sometimes failures can mean you get out of breath, or empty your bank account.', 'Rules'=>'The Character must pay / lose 32 Facet Sway.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Transformation', 'Type'=>'Weakened', 'Description'=>'Failures when transforming something can compound upon the transformed Character or Descendant.', 'Rules'=>'Creates a new Hitch, or increases a pre-existing Hitch by 1 Bane, or decreases 1 Facet (or Annex for a Descendant) by 1 Boon.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Failures', 'Category'=>'Wellness', 'Type'=>'Hurt', 'Description'=>'Failures can compound, creating a more grievous injury.', 'Rules'=>'Hurt Failures Draw and Play 2 Cards as an Attack on the Character at the current Stakes. This Attack can be Soaked as usual.'),

		array('Level'=>'2 Successes', 'Category'=>'Cards', 'Type'=>'Destiny', 'Description'=>'Flashes of inspiration can come at any time, bringing a glimpse of a single possible future.', 'Rules'=>'The Character may Draw an additional Wyrd Tarot Card into their Hand.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Successes', 'Category'=>'Combat', 'Type'=>'Snap-fire', 'Description'=>'Compounding success in combat can create a situation where the Tide of Battle is decided by a snap-fire decision, a single shot, or single blow.', 'Rules'=>'The current Ordeal spawns a separate Snap-fire Ordeal. The Snap-fire Ordeal decides the Tide of Battle for the original Ordeal, usually based on a single Snap-fire Phase.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Successes', 'Category'=>'Communication', 'Type'=>'Rapport', 'Description'=>'Sometimes communication can go so well that two people seem to have an almost telepathic communication, reading micro-expressions, unconscious communication channels, shared contextual clues, code phrases and the like.', 'Rules'=>'The Communication allows two Characters to speak about one subject, or even remain silent, while exchanging notes separately. These notes cannot be intercepted, except potentially by actual psychic abilities. The Characters can respond to the note physically at the end of the exchange, or may coordinate actions with a "Now!" or whatever.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Successes', 'Category'=>'Complexity', 'Type'=>'Havoc’s Hope', 'Description'=>'Success in complex situations can create opportunities within the chaos. Where some see chaos, confusion, bedlam, turmoil, pandemonium, and havoc, others see chances, convenience, benefits, tactical options, possibilities and hope.', 'Rules'=>'Havoc’s Hope Successes alter an Ordeal, offering some alternate route through the Ordeal. This is often a 1 Card "shortcut" of some sort, that cuts out at least two Stages or 1 Stage and an Obstacle.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Successes', 'Category'=>'Descendant', 'Type'=>'Back-up', 'Description'=>'When using a Descendant, Success can sometimes mean finding a spare battery, a second clip or even a duplicate weapon.', 'Rules'=>'The Character typically makes a Gain of either a duplicate of a Descendant they are already using, or a suitable Descendant to replace, reload or recharge that Descendant.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Successes', 'Category'=>'Dramatic', 'Type'=>'Distressing', 'Description'=>'Dramatic Successes can compound and reinforce, making this very distressing for those also in the Scene.', 'Rules'=>'The Character may upgrade 1 of the Ordeal cards they played on another Character (typically as a Psych Attack) into a Distress Card. This works as usual, but if the target does not have enough Stress to purchase the Distress Card, they instead of taking a Trauma add the Pips as Stress and Discard the Distress Card.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Successes', 'Category'=>'Emotional', 'Type'=>'Effusive', 'Description'=>'Emotional Successes can compound, making a Character seem over-flowing with emotions that others cannot help but be swayed by.', 'Rules'=>'Creates a 2 Card Psych Effect (such as Wonder or Terror) on all other Characters that are present. Typically this will be a Positive emotion for the Character (Wonder, Trust, Assured, etc) and their Allies and a Negative emotion (Terror, Unsatisfied, Concerned) for their enemies.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Successes', 'Category'=>'Environmental', 'Type'=>'Paradigm Shift', 'Description'=>'Sometimes a succession of Successes can usher in a change of enormous proportions, that changes everything. These are known as Paradigm Shifts. ', 'Rules'=>'During a Paradigm Shift the culture or Location makes a Change of Social Age. The Yarn-Teller typically selects the Social Age that has now begun from one of the Cards played in the Action, or the card atop the Discard Pile.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Successes', 'Category'=>'Investigation', 'Type'=>'Evidence', 'Description'=>'Successes in an investigation can lead a Character to unearthing actual evidence, something that shows a truth, a clue to what really happened.', 'Rules'=>'Evidence Successes unearth Clues, which can indicate a hint from the Yarn-Teller or Referee, or reveal a missed or overlooked Revelation.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Successes', 'Category'=>'Logical', 'Type'=>'Syllogism', 'Description'=>'Compounding Logical Successes can lead you from two propositions to a final conclusion that also must be true.', 'Rules'=>'Syllogism Successes allow a Character to make a "true" statement that will be treated as true by the Setting (subject to the Settings rules, the Yarn-Teller, etc), the statement must come as a conclusion based on two propositional sentences,  that have been agreed by the Character and Yarn-Teller.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Successes', 'Category'=>'Narrative', 'Type'=>'Conflict-working', 'Description'=>'Compounding Narrative Successes can work the central conflict directly, grant a Character a sense of relief and rest from a Weft Scene, or their opposition being granted a Warp Scene.', 'Rules'=>'The Character may be granted a Weft (which may also include a Gain, or Revelation). Alternatively the opposed Embodiments may take a Warp Scene instead (including both Snag and Fray). Warp or Weft the Scene is usually defined by the Ordeal Cards the Character played (or may be drawn by the Yarn-Teller and Played for free).'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Successes', 'Category'=>'Proficiency', 'Type'=>'Creative', 'Description'=>'A multiplicity of success can sometimes not just grant you knowledge of a subject, but grant you knowledge of a subject that did not even exist until you just thought of it. This is how new subjects for study are discovered, invented and explored.', 'Rules'=>'The Character can Gain a new Proficiency that they create for this specific situation. New Proficiencies must be suitable to the Tapestry, including Era, Setting and Genre.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Successes', 'Category'=>'Psychosocial', 'Type'=>'Impressive', 'Description'=>'Whenever a Character displays great mastery at something, even if they do not actually succeed, it can have a powerful impact of people’s impressions of you.', 'Rules'=>'All Characters that witnessed the Action improve their Impression of the Character by 2 Levels.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Successes', 'Category'=>'Score', 'Type'=>'Mighty', 'Description'=>'If all you are doing is accumulating Score then at least you can try to Score a Mighty Success.', 'Rules'=>'Mighty Successes add 92 Banal Score (+16 Chi/Pips).'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Successes', 'Category'=>'Stress', 'Type'=>'Respite', 'Description'=>'Successes can stack causing a massive respite from stress and tension. ', 'Rules'=>'Respite Success Relieves 16 Stress, 5 Strains, or 2 Shocks, or 1 Shock, 2 Strains and 6 Stress simultaneously instantly.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Successes', 'Category'=>'Sway', 'Type'=>'Chi', 'Description'=>'Multiple Successes can generate Chi for the Character.', 'Rules'=>'The Character makes a normal Chi Gain for their type.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Successes', 'Category'=>'Transformation', 'Type'=>'Smooth', 'Description'=>'During a Transformation, multiple successes combine to make the transformation smooth. This is not always a perfect transformation, but it is consistent, and painless.', 'Rules'=>'Smooth Successes indicate a transformation that is pain-free and difficult to spot. Whatever the Character or Descendant has transformed into it has broadly assumed that form, and function (including all the Annexes normally associated with that form). A Character who has become a blackbird would look like a blackbird at least to anyone who wasn’t also a blackbird, and they should be able to fly and sing.'),
		array('Level'=>'2 Successes', 'Category'=>'Wellness', 'Type'=>'Stabilized', 'Description'=>'Sometimes Success when you are injured or wounded, can just mean that things don’t get any worse for you, at least for a little while.', 'Rules'=>'All Fresh Wounds the Character has are instantly Naturally Stabilised, they will count as though they were one Wound Class lower until they can be healed or fixed.'),

		array('Level'=>'5 Failures', 'Category'=>'Cards', 'Type'=>'Condemned', 'Description'=>'Sometimes a whole load of failures can stack up, creating truly terrible consequences for the Character. They may find themselves condemned to prison, bound by a geas, or occasionally put to death.', 'Rules'=>'The Yarn-Teller may use any cards the Character has played as Yarn-Cards to create a Plight, Quest or Geas upon the Character. If the Yarn-Teller doesn’t feel up to creating a whole Spread then they could just alter the Significator of the current Scene. Or create a Fray, Snag or Warp for the Character instead.'),
        array('Level'=>'5 Failures', 'Category'=>'Cards', 'Type'=>'Blinded', 'Description'=>'Sometimes a catalogue of failures can result in a Character becoming momentarily blinded, doom-blind, or confused.', 'Rules'=>'Cards in the Ordeal Pool and Wyrd Tarot Hand, should be immediately shuffled together and then dealt back out, facedown on the table. These cards may only be played blind (with new Draws also face-down) until all face-down cards have been played (especially from the Wyrd Tarot Hand). Doomblind Characters must assign Wyrd Tarot Cards or Yarn Cards to targets or effects, before revealing the card. In the case of Wyrd Tarot, they can be then reversed '),
		array('Level'=>'5 Failures', 'Category'=>'Combat', 'Type'=>'Contact', 'Description'=>'It is said that no plan survives first contact with the enemy, or to put it another way, everyone has a plan, until they get hit. A great combat plan makes no difference if the enemy don’t respond as you predicted, and the only good planning is levels of contingency and not relying on a single soldier.', 'Rules'=>'Contact Failures cause all of the Character’s Prepared Cards, including their Style Reserve, (but not Wyrd Tarot Hand, Monster Pool or Ordeal Pool cards) to be discarded.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Failures', 'Category'=>'Communication', 'Type'=>'Misunderstanding', 'Description'=>'When multiple failures occur during communication, Characters can get entirely the wrong idea about what you are trying to communicate. This can be a simple inversion, but is usually much worse than just the wrong way around.', 'Rules'=>'The original message is completely destroyed. Instead a new message that has no bearing on the original context at all is created. This new message is often completely antithetical to what was originally intended, without just being the opposite, and usually has some emotional impact (up to 2 cards). E.g. "Please, my family and I need food" is misunderstood as "My family are animals and we are trying to rob, murder and eat you" with a side order of 2 cards of Terror.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Failures', 'Category'=>'Complexity', 'Type'=>'Havoc', 'Description'=>'Complex systems are especially noted for their ability to become completely unstable, chaotic and run out of control. Multiple failures while trying to control the complex can result in a situation where the machinery or system will not respond to any attempt to control it, and it begins operating at random.', 'Rules'=>'Complex systems can fly out of control. Selecting a random target(s), and affecting them with random Annexes, or random effects that are still based upon the Root or Channel of the Annexes being used. Typically a system that is suffering Havoc Failure cannot have control regained, and must be at least tactically Maimed, carefully Crippled or just destroyed to stop it.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Failures', 'Category'=>'Descendant', 'Type'=>'Exploded', 'Description'=>'Descendants can go wrong in spectacular ways, sometimes. For example, fail to clean a gun properly, fail to load it properly, with imprecise manufactured bullets, add some dodgy electronics, no firearm safety instructions, and then hand said gun to an idiot and see what happens. These sorts of Descendant Failures are quite rare and should only be used if a Character has not been maintaining a Descendant properly, before the compounded Failures.', 'Rules'=>'The Descendant Draws and Plays 5 Cards as an attack upon itself and its user (as an additional target).'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Failures', 'Category'=>'Dramatic', 'Type'=>'Dramatic Hazard', 'Description'=>'Drama can creates Hazards, both big and small, but when lots of failure swirls in the air, and something Dramatic is happening, you can bet that a Dramatic Hazard is on the cards for someone, and they usually aren’t looking at a little Snag that is going to be a minor complication.', 'Rules'=>'The Character must take a Hazard, as though they had rolled a Hazard Drama. However, due to the extreme nature of the Dramatic Hazard Failure this Hazard will be at least a Plight or Fray, and can create a Sub-Plot, Geas or Quest.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Failures', 'Category'=>'Emotional', 'Type'=>'Heart-wrenching', 'Description'=>'Emotional failures can compound in ways that can lead Characters to the very depths of heart-wrenching feelings, emotions so powerful that Characters can wish they were dead rather than experiencing them. Or their enemies may experience such a high that they chuckle or smile, whenever they remember it, for the rest of their days...', 'Rules'=>'The Character will take a 3 Card (Extreme) Negative Psych Effect or an opposed Embodiment Character will take a 3 Card (Extreme) Positive Psych Effect.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Failures', 'Category'=>'Environmental', 'Type'=>'Catastrophe', 'Description'=>'Sometimes failures in a Location can have a detrimental effect on the Location, usually a few failures will have limited effect on the Location, perhaps creating a few marks or something, but enough failures, all at once, can have a powerfully negative effect on the environment, even wiping the Location from existence.', 'Rules'=>'The Location Draws and Plays 5 cards upon itself and every Character within, as an environmental attack, such as an avalanche, collapse, cave-in, earthquake, fire, flooding, landslide, sky-fall, tsunami, etc. Sometimes Catastrophe Failures will instead of creating a single attack they will instead create a Force-Of-Nature Monster (upto VII) Extra, or a Giant to represent the Catastrophe. This Force-Of-Nature or Giant will usually have a Size similar to the Location targeted (a little bit smaller or larger than the Location as the Yarn-Teller requires). For example, a Forest Fire will not start out as large as the forest, but grows larger over time, as more is burned; a mudslide or avalanche off a mountain will be smaller than the mountain, but still much bigger than the hotel on the slopes.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Failures', 'Category'=>'Investigation', 'Type'=>'Misinformation', 'Description'=>'Make enough mistakes in an investigation, treating misinformation as information, red herrings as clues, and clues as red herrings and you will come to a completely incorrect conclusion. What is more, once you share your inaccurate conclusion, it will be misinformation itself.', 'Rules'=>'Misinformation Failures cause a Character to come to an incorrect conclusion. The Yarn-Teller may narrate this incorrect conclusion directly, or simply misinform the Character of the "facts" and allow the Player to come to some incorrect conclusion. It should be noted though that Misinformation Failures also create a moderated retcon, that changes some aspect of the history, so the original facts cannot be recovered (even by time travel) this can create an unresolvable paradox.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Failures', 'Category'=>'Logical', 'Type'=>'Logical Hitch', 'Description'=>'Enough Logical Failures can cause a Character to internalise these failures, which can of course lead to ongoing biases and even irrational behaviours.', 'Rules'=>'Logical Hitch Failures involve a Character talking themselves into a new Hitch with Bane 7 (spending 30 Chi to increase the Bane of a new Quirk).'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Failures', 'Category'=>'Narrative', 'Type'=>'Monstrosity', 'Description'=>'Sometimes a number of narrative failures can compound, such that a Character finds things out about themselves that they never wanted to know, most people are uncomfortable enough when another views them as a monster, imagine how terrible it must feel to realise you really are the monster.', 'Rules'=>'Monstrosity Failures typically create a 6 Card Yarn Geas Spread, that includes a Quest, Revelation and Lore, that will usually include a Monster Facet or five. The Quest defines the monstrous goal of the Character and the Lore defines some Monstrous Annex the Character develops.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Failures', 'Category'=>'Proficiency', 'Type'=>'Dangerous Knowledge', 'Description'=>'It is said that a little knowledge is a dangerous thing, multiple small mistakes can create a terrible result for the Character.', 'Rules'=>'Dangerous Knowledge Draws and Plays 5 Cards as an Attack on the Character, as a result of their dumb choices.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Failures', 'Category'=>'Psychosocial', 'Type'=>'Pariah', 'Description'=>'Multiple failures in any social context can make a Character a pariah who no one wants to be around. This can even extend to their mindscape where their Self can become a pariah among their inner lives.', 'Rules'=>'The Yarn-Teller can pull and play 5 Ordeal Cards upon the Character in any Psychosocial Space. This can alter Social Ordeal Levels or create Obstacles around their Self in the Mindscape, that should negatively impact their social life. '),
		array('Level'=>'5 Failures', 'Category'=>'Score', 'Type'=>'Collapse', 'Description'=>'When multiple failures occur when you are trying your hardest, you can mostly end up getting in your own way.', 'Rules'=>'Collapse Failures cause the generated Score to be Halved.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Failures', 'Category'=>'Stress', 'Type'=>'Snapped', 'Description'=>'Stress can build up very quickly when small mistakes are being made, and faster when the mistakes are larger, a few people can cope with this level of stress but for most this will result in a camel’s back and straw situation.', 'Rules'=>'Snapped Failures cause the Character to take 3 Shocks, 8 Strains or 32 Stress in one heap of failure.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Failures', 'Category'=>'Sway', 'Type'=>'Debt', 'Description'=>'Sometimes when you are trying to generate a little wealth quickly, you can end up owing more than you borrowed in the first place. Now imagine what happens when you make that mistake repeatedly.', 'Rules'=>'Debt Failures allow a Character to create the normal amount of Sway. However, the Character has placed themselves in debt somehow to create that wealth. The Debt must be paid in full within the Extend Duration, or a whole Sub-Plot will be triggered about the Debt. These Debts usually have an interest rate that causes the Debt to compound every time the Limit Duration expires. E.g. Generate 41 Chi and you have 8 Months to pay it back, however every 19 Hours the debt adds another 41 Chi.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Failures', 'Category'=>'Transformation', 'Type'=>'Abomination', 'Description'=>'If there is one time when failure is a terrible idea, it is when you are shape-shifting or transforming someone else.', 'Rules'=>'The Yarn-Teller is free to make the transformation as miserable as possible with A Hitch of 9 Banes (45 Chi), Monster Facets or a 6 Card Geas Spread.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Failures', 'Category'=>'Wellness', 'Type'=>'Wrecked', 'Description'=>'Too many failures can be bad for your health.', 'Rules'=>'Wrecked Failures Draw and Play 3 Ordeal Cards on the Character at the current Stakes. These cards are Unsoakable, and may be split into separate WOunds or combined as the Yarn-Teller decides.'),

		array('Level'=>'5 Successes', 'Category'=>'Cards', 'Type'=>'Yarn-Spinning', 'Description'=>'Sometimes things go so well that it can almost feel like magic.', 'Rules'=>'Yarn-Telling Successes allow Characters to play cards as Yarn Cards, creating Yarn Spreads on the Target, or the current Scene. This is often used to change the Significator of the current Scene. Yarn-Tellers may narrate the result of their Yarn Card Play otherwise the exact interpretation will up to the current Narrating Yarn-Teller or Referee.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Successes', 'Category'=>'Combat', 'Type'=>'Counter-Offensive', 'Description'=>'Successes in Combat can place a Character in exactly the right place at the right time to completely disrupt an enemies plans with something as simple as a taunt or punch on the face.', 'Rules'=>'The Target is staggered by the Counter-Offensive, causing them Discard all Ordeal Pool cards and cards Prepared for active Actions (you can keep the cards you spent digging in, putting on your field plate armour, or piling sandbags).'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Successes', 'Category'=>'Communication', 'Type'=>'Psychosocial-nexus', 'Description'=>'Compounding communication successes goes beyond normal levels of rapport and enters the areas of actual telepathy, at least it can feel like it. Such closeness can allow subconscious and even psychic (Setting allowing) communication channels to open between two Characters.', 'Rules'=>'Characters that are this close have their Psychosocial Mindscapes connecting, usually becoming Attached to each other, they are normally connected via Folks, but other connections are possible, such as Humour, Passions or Darkness functioning as the bridge state.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Successes', 'Category'=>'Complexity', 'Type'=>'Convoluted', 'Description'=>'Complex systems and machines can achieve amazing things when they are used correctly, they can do things that no one even originally imagined they could, with a little successful fiddling here and there. Great successes when working with such systems can create convolutions that impede the targets from even working out what is happening until it is too late.', 'Rules'=>'Convoluted Successes can make a system capable of using magical difficulties even if technological, increasing the capabilities dramatically for a while. Additionally the Convoluted Success can create a Serious Obstacle (3 Cards) that can impede the target even understanding they have been targeted.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Successes', 'Category'=>'Descendant', 'Type'=>'Virtuosity', 'Description'=>'Great success when using a tool or instrument, is known as virtuosity, and can make even the simplest tools seem capable of amazing things.', 'Rules'=>'Virtuosity Successes allow a Descendant to Draw and Play an additional 5 Cards. However they can play up to 3 of these cards as Unsoakable, or they may play 3 as an Psych Effect upon those that witness to the Action, or they can play 3 as a new Serious Obstacle in the Stage.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Successes', 'Category'=>'Dramatic', 'Type'=>'Tempest', 'Description'=>'Dramatic Success can create a situation where it can seem that everyone seems to get some Drama around the Character.', 'Rules'=>'The Character may Draw 7 Ordeal Cards and play them as Drama cards on any Characters present in the Scene, including themselves. This will Relieve Stress as usual for the Characters effected by the Drama cards. The Tempest Success also empties the Drama Pool as though Drama had been rolled.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Successes', 'Category'=>'Emotional', 'Type'=>'Exalting', 'Description'=>'When enough emotional successes stack a Character can powerfully effect multiple other people’s emotional states.', 'Rules'=>'Exalting Successes typically cause those Characters who are witnessing the Action to be affected by a 3 Card Psych Effect (soaked as usual). The Succeeding Character can decide whether they wish to cause a Positive or Negative Emotion, and may split so that allies feel Positive emotions and enemies Negative emotions if they wish.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Successes', 'Category'=>'Environmental', 'Type'=>'Transcendent', 'Description'=>'When everything about a place is just perfect a place can take on a sacred, sublime, numinous, hallowed or even utopian aspect. Great Success can generate this same feeling, as though the world has been stretched thin and the gods shine through the fabric.', 'Rules'=>'Transcendent Successes can make a Descendant (including a Location or Pact) feel as though it has been touched by the divine. This can allow a Character to attune to the Location or Descendant as though they were the owner or a member, allowing them to gain access to Edges and Glows the Descendant may have (if only for a short time). Transcendent Successes can also allow a Character to alter their type Extra to Grunt, Grunt to Hero, Hero to Yarn-Yeller, etc.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Successes', 'Category'=>'Investigation', 'Type'=>'Cracked-It', 'Description'=>'Sometimes multiple successes can reveal the complete story of what happened, who did it, and even why.', 'Rules'=>'The Character may Draw and Play 5 Cards as a Revelation Spread, this Spread should be focused on revealing the truth about the situation they are investigating, who the bad guy really is, and perhaps what their weaknesses are, although the current Yarn-Teller can throw in additional details if they wish. '),
		array('Level'=>'5 Successes', 'Category'=>'Logical', 'Type'=>'Argumentation', 'Description'=>'The amazing thing about Logical successes is that while each component has a simple task such as exposing some fact or draws a conclusion from logical premises, each Success is also building upon the last, joining facts together into a network of logical conclusions, that define a logical argument.', 'Rules'=>'The Character may Draw 6 and Play 5 Cards as a Logical Argumentation. This is a special logical Attack that represents both a Psych Attack and a "Magic" Attack, that has a goal of convincing the Target of an arguments truth, this is most often done with Lecture attacks. Rather than "Wounding" in the traditional sense, the Attack tries to convince the Character of the argument (and can move them in their own Mindscape, affect them with Emotions, or create Hitches as required).'), 
		array('Level'=>'5 Successes', 'Category'=>'Narrative', 'Type'=>'Accomplishment', 'Description'=>'Sometimes the accumulated successes accomplish something for the Character that they were not even trying to achieve.', 'Rules'=>'Accomplishment Successes cause a Character to achieve something they were not attempting with their Action. At its simplest a Character should make a Gain based on the Card atop the Discard Pile, or a Revelation based off the Cards they played or the Wild Pool, although they could just pass a Test they are not consciously attempting (such as passing some moral exam when they refuse to finish off their opponent).'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Successes', 'Category'=>'Proficiency', 'Type'=>'Maven', 'Description'=>'Those truly adept at something, the aces, wizards and mavens of their field can accomplish things that others would never attempt.', 'Rules'=>'Maven Successes allow a Character to purchase new Proficiencies during an Action, this can allow them to add a Proficiency Die (up to 3), or add additional Proficiencies into an Annex they are currently using, adding Umbrals, Nimbeds or Extra Slot Proficiencies. Maven Successes have and effective Chi of 42 and the costs to add Proficiencies vary as follows, Skill = 3 (can only fill Extra Slots), Talent = 6 (Aura Slots and Extra Slots), Power = 8 and Super-Annex = 13. A Maven Success can therefore add at most  14 Skill Extra Slots, 7 Talent Profs, 5 Power Profs, or 3 Super-Annex Profs. Additionally Hitches can also store Proficiencies and a Maven Success should top any missing Hitch Proficiency Slots too.'),//editPoint
		array('Level'=>'5 Successes', 'Category'=>'Psychosocial', 'Type'=>'Transmundane', 'Description'=>'Great Success when dealing with a Psychosocial plane can lead a Character to experiencing that plane directly. This can involve a Character experiencing their mindscape or some spirit world or underworld overtly, seeing it around them, noting its denizens and seeing their paths. For the Bulm&auml;s they may perceive a Character’s Soul-Path, seeing memories replay from past-lives.', 'Rules'=>'The Character is effectively moved from their real world position to some Psychosocial State (or back). Typically they still exist in the real world, but this is dependant upon the Yarn-Teller. Their perceptions fully reveal the Psychosocial Space, letting them view things in the distance, see Archetypes or Psychosocial Characters in that space and travel consciously where ever they wish. They may still have some residual comprehension of the real world if they are actually conscious during this experience.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Successes', 'Category'=>'Score', 'Type'=>'Two-fold', 'Description'=>'Sometimes successes can compound and expand and instead of the result you sought you get something much better and bigger, twice as successful as you thought.', 'Rules'=>'A Two-fold Success doubles the Score rolled, regardless of other factors (this can cause shifts in the number of Failure and Success Levels).'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Successes', 'Category'=>'Stress', 'Type'=>'Second-wind', 'Description'=>'Sometimes when you are working hard, you might hit a wall where you feel you cannot go past it and have to stop, other times this wall will melt away, and you get a second wind.', 'Rules'=>'Second-wind Successes allow a Character to Relieve all current Stress, Strains and Shocks instantly.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Successes', 'Category'=>'Sway', 'Type'=>'Inflection-point', 'Description'=>'Sometimes great activity and profound works can lead to a sea-change, paradigm-shift or inflection point after which the world seems always different.', 'Rules'=>'Inflection-point Successes allow a Character to alter the Setting. Typically this is used to make the Facet Sway being generated have greater Potency in the setting (although it can also limit Potency too). For example if Support is Banal in the Setting then an Inflection-point Success could make Support Intrepid from now on, as the Character succeeds in some sort of political or democratic reforms.'),
		array('Level'=>'5 Successes', 'Category'=>'Transformation', 'Type'=>'Protean', 'Description'=>'Transformation is normally about making one thing into something else, mostly they are permanent and static transformations. Protean transformations are neither permanent nor static.', 'Rules'=>'Protean Successes grant the target of a Transformation Action the ability to transform between the selected new form and their original form, or the transformation can be continuos for the Duration allowing the target to change shapes. '),
		array('Level'=>'5 Successes', 'Category'=>'Wellness', 'Type'=>'Shrug-off', 'Description'=>'Sometimes success means that the Character may be hit, struck down, and all may seem lost, but then they come surging back, driven by some powerful need for retribution, or desire to protect another, shrugging-off bullets and explosives as scratches.', 'Rules'=>'Shrug-off Successes Remove all Wounds the Character currently suffers from below the level of Carnage. Carnage Wounds typically require a Retcon event at least to undo.'),


    );
  
