    public static $deathTypes = array(
        array(
            'Type' => 'The End',
            'Description' => 'Death is the end, after life ceases there is no afterlife of any sort. There is no reincarnation or continuation.',
            'Rules' => 'Dead Characters are essentially replaced with a Physical Descendant called "X’s Corpse" or similar.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Spirit',
            'Description' => 'Death is not the end. Something of the Character is preserved after their life is ended as they are transferred to a new spiritual plane as a Spirit.',
            'Rules' => 'The Yarn burst that is released upon death must be enough to purchase a change of Formation Facet, from Nature (Flesh or whatever really) to Awe (Spirit). Spirits may learn to explore the spirit worlds, and some cosmologies and religions will allow the return to living realm (in some form).'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Reincarnation',
            'Description' => 'Death is not the end, those who die are immediately reincarnated as a new born baby. Sometimes there is some lingering memories from this previous life, but usually these memories are hidden away and not experienced until this new Character gains access to memories from that Alternate, or previous life.',
            'Rules' => 'Characters who die must immediately create a new Alt as a Scale -4 new born, this Character may learn to access Proficiencies and Annexes from their previous incarnations.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Purgatory',
            'Description' => 'Purgatory is a spiritual realm where the dead are purified before entrance to the Heavenly Afterlife. This existence varies from religion to religion, from a heavenly waiting room, to a hellish land of trials that the soul must complete. In some religions and cosmologies failure to pass to the heavens may result in falling to Hell or another round of re-incarnation.',
            'Rules' => 'Characters who die are converted to spirits. They may then be tested or simply have to wait in line, accumulating more Sway of various types, before they are allowed access to another spiritual realm or create a new Alt reincarnation.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Paradise',
            'Description' => 'Paradise, Nirvana or Heaven, is a promised state, usually offered to the faithful of particular religions. This paradise offers a world free from suffering, but only the worthy may enter. So there is often a step of Testing the spirit, by whatever rules the deities responsible have decided. Those who do not enter may be offered some alternate afterlife, or reincarnation.',
            'Rules' => 'Characters who die are converted to spirits which are then tested, if found worthy they are granted access to a spiritual realm of some divinity or religion.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Hell',
            'Description' => 'Some religions have a place of punishment, where souls may be damned for eternity. The spirits that are sent there are usually tormented for their sins in life. In some cases they are punished by fallen angels or demons, in others they suffer alongside these same beings.',
            'Rules' => 'Characters who die are converted into a spirit, they may be judged in another realm, or simply be sent to Hell, where they will be judged and punished for a period of time that can be as long as eternity (and may feel like it even if it isn’t), often by the order of a benevolent god. Sometimes punishments are made to fit the crime poetically, in these cases should the spirit manage to learn from this lesson they move on to another plane.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Underworld',
            'Description' => 'The lands of the dead are given a geographical location here, the dead live beneath the earth. This conceptual land of the dead is where all buried bodies spirits are collected, whether brought there by a ferryman or entombed. The exact nature of this underworld life varies from cosmology to cosmology, with some rulers of the dead acting simply as landlords, others as prison wardens, and appears to predate the conceptions of paradise and hell.',
            'Rules' => 'Characters who die are converted into a spirit, they may then guided by another spirit (a psychopomp) into the appropriate part of the underworld.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Shades',
            'Description' => 'When an Increated eats the soul of a living being, this does not technically kill them. In fact, the Increated technically don’t consume souls, instead they steal the whole living being, sometimes they will leave a corpse behind, but often this will be yet another Increated playing a role. Those taken by the Increated are "stimulated" to create Sway for the Increated, by whatever methods the Increated has discovered, which often depends upon what the victim believes has happened to them.',
            'Rules' => 'Alts removed by Increated are taken to Shades where they are used to construct and maintain the realms the Increated keep there. It is impossible for any being in Shades to die, although escape may be possible in other ways.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'F&aelig; Otherworld',
            'Description' => 'Those of F&arlig;ry blood, when they die immediately reincarnate in the Otherworld of the F&aelig; there they will live another whole life, usually as a Commoner, before they die and reincarnate back to the so-called world of men. What’s more this Otherworld and the "Real" world share each other as a "dreamworld" where they may experience past-future or even concurrent lives.',
            'Rules' => 'Upon death the Character immediately creates a new Alt in the Otherworld, when this Alt sleeps it will dream of the real world and may even appear in it. Once this Character is dead in the Otherworld they will return to real world. It may be noted that both worlds do not share the exact same sense of time usually, the days of elves are weeks, months, years and even centuries to men according to some sources.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Bulm&auml;s Cycle',
            'Description' => 'Bulm&auml;s are also known as soul-eaters, as they are able to consume the souls of others and add their knowledge and abilities to their own. Traditionally, the Bulm&auml;s only consumed the souls of other Bulm&auml;s, as only these spirits had enough power and experience for the Bulm&auml;s to make sense of them. However, Labyrinth Walkers, Broccen and Hunters have all eaten human souls to learn from them from time to time. Eventually all Bulm&auml;s souls tend to collect in Vermis, who uses these millions of souls, to seed new worlds with Bulm&auml;s. All-Walkers have the ability to read and "duplicate" souls, allowing them to add a copy of another’s soul to their own collection.',
            'Rules' => 'Bulm&auml;s Characters may add Alts to their own being, tying on the soul threads with differing degrees of Integration. Integration has a strong similarity component for Bulm&auml;s, with most consumed souls becoming Subsumed automatically.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Cyberwraith',
            'Description' => 'The Eusaivean Nano, and later Femite, technology allowed Eusaiveans minds to be uploaded into a sophisticated computer simulation. Eventually this technology became an automatic process, continually backing up a Eusaivean mind. These uploaded minds continue service as Cyberwraiths, operating robotic bodies as well as biological ones.',
            'Rules' => 'Upon death the Character’s Incarna is converted to either Orthodox (Data) or Heresy (Fiction), depending upon their preference. As a Cyberwraith they will be able to infest, pilot or interact with machines and Femite or even Nullite systems.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Nephillim Cradle',
            'Description' => 'Developed from Eusaivean Femite technology, but an improvement in every way. The Nephillim Cradle creates a virtual afterlife that spreads via Nullite technology to upload minds automatically that die within its domain. Uploaded minds are usually sorted by various religious and moral criteria into the afterlife they expected, although with enough variance to make them believe it to be true.',
            'Rules' => 'Upon death the Character’s Incarna is converted to either Awe (Spirit), Enigma (Riddle), Heresy (Fiction), Key (Inspiration), Liberty (Dream), Orthodox (Data), Trial (Metal), Virtue (Energy), Wyrd (Fate), or Zeal (Faith), depending upon their preference. These beings may be considered Cyberwraiths, Living Souls, Fairies, or Nephillim as required by those controlling the Cradle.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Quantum Immortality',
            'Description' => 'Some Heroes when they are confronted by death simply refuse. In that moment of death they reach out and find a nearby universe that is pretty close to the one that just became unsurvivable and they move there, becoming nothing more than a weird moment in that new persons memory. Other ways this can work is reaching across to find an uninjured version of yourself from another universe and pull them across to yours, so that you can miraculously survive unsurvivable things.',
            'Rules' => 'The Yarn release upon death is used to either side-step their consciousness to a nearby universe that is as close as possible to the one the Character is currently dying in, or to find a suitable alternate in another universe who can be substituted into the current untenable situation allowing it to be survived. This Alt is usually so similar that they will automatically integrate together, and they may not even notice. Sometimes the Yarn-burst itself can be enough to remove all the Character’s Wounds and change their Hitches from "Dying" or "Dead" to Scarred or something similar, or even remove them.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Living Death',
            'Description' => 'The dead are aware of what happens to them, this may be due to a failure of a nephillim cradle, or a spirit becoming locked to its material body.',
            'Rules' => 'If a Character does not have enough Chi upon Death to convert them into another form or sidestep on death they may enter the Living Death. Often the living death with resolve when their body is finally destroyed or one of their Hitches grows to a Woe, when they will move to Undeath.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Undeath',
            'Description' => 'Some dark powers and terrible situations can lead a Character to a Fate worse than death.',
            'Rules' => 'Those who die with a Woe Hitch can elect to convert that Woe into "Undead" or "Undying". This Woe will limit the conditions of this Undeath (often adding Taboos), but will also often add a Lore that defines their type of Undead.'
        ) ,
    );

    public static $gamePlayTypes = array( // this is not how I want to do it.
        // array('Type'=>'Wargaming', 'Description'=>'The original form of play in roleplaying is that of Wargaming, with each player controlling an army of models on a tabletop. This style is still played by some players, but has little to no roleplaying, this is a tactical and strategic game with no narrative.', 'Rules'=>'Wargames are played with miniatures and battleboard maps, they emphasise simulationist resolution and have limited narratives. Such games are usually played within a single extended Ordeal.'),
        // array('Type'=>'Crawling', 'Description'=>'Based heavily on the wargaming that preceded it, crawling is the original play-style favoured by Gygax. Players control a single character at low level (although "player controlled" NPCs, or Secondary Characters, such as hired swords will raise this number). The Referee is always in charge of running the Crawl (whether a Dungeon Crawl, City Crawl, or Wilderness game), but there is limited Narrative here anyway, with most of the Narrative emerging from traps, monster fights and accidents. Players usually explain their actions in third person, as there is limited "roleplaying".', 'Rules'=>'Crawling is based around simulationist challenges, which are equivalent to T13’s Ordeals and Tests. Challenges are balanced in difficulty solely by the level of the Character, which at its most basic is either a measure of how much wealth has passed through the character’s purses (equivalent to Scale in T13), how many monsters they have beaten (killed a few level 1 monsters? Welcome to Level 2), or the deepest level of a dungeon they have survived (you have delved below Level 6?! Can I touch you, for luck?), depending on the setting and game. PCs are usually limited to Grunt characters.'),
        // array('Type'=>'LARP', 'Description'=>'Live Action Role-Playing appears on the scene during the late 60s, but later merged theories from improvisational drama and comedy with Crawling to create a style of fantasy roleplay where players physically portray their character. LARP systems are generally held distinct from table-top systems as more emphasis is placed on the acting and therefore the Player’s skill than necessarily the character’s abilities, task resolution is often completely simulationist (such as LARP sword fighting, or string traps) or entirely abstract (such as rock, paper, scissors acting as a psychic power challenge or replacing fighting to reduce injury risk). LARP emphasises character interactions, portrayal and immersion as aspects of the player experience. Referees are still expected to create the scenario, rig traps, portray NPCs, etc, and for this reason most LARPs include multiple Referees and additional NPC actors (sometimes called Assistant Refs or similar) who will portray a number of different NPCs throughout the scenario.', 'Rules'=>'T13 is not designed for pure LARP play, but feel free to develop LARP applications of the system yourself.'),
        // array('Type'=>'Heroics', 'Description'=>'Heroic play developed in the late 1970s partially as a continuation of Crawling’s move away from Wargaming. The idea became that each player character should be like the hero of their own story, and that the goal of the game was to create a satisfying narrative. This led to a greater inclusion of narrative styles, and a move away from simulationist mechanics towards a more flexible and less crunchy, smoother game flow that emphasised character portrayal and immersion. Referees are still in charge of the narrative, mostly represented as a series of challenges, but all players add to the narration by speaking "in-character" as much as possible, and may even add first-person narration. All Players are encouraged to work toward building a story.', 'Rules'=>'Generally less simulationist, more narrative style play. Heroes are allowed as player characters who can directly effect the narrative in minor ways. Players are encouraged to play their role, and Referees are encouraged to work in story-lines for each character, usually in the form of Character Rivals, Enemies and Nemeses.'),
        // array('Type'=>'Larp', 'Description'=>'Larp emerges from LARP by way of the Nordic countries. The Nordic Larp tradition places even more emphasis on character portrayal, collaboration and collective story-telling, rather than a Referee or NPC led story. This requires unobtrusive rules to determine success or failure without a significant loss of immersion as no Referee is necessarily present to determine the course of events. Characters are defined by personality traits rather than simulationist statistics, and there is a breadth to play that can vary from light-hearted romp to thematically heavy grim-dark sagas. Genre-wise Larp has moved away from traditional fantasy settings to embrace more modern genres such as magic-realism and supernatural horror.', 'Rules'=>'Larp characters are usually Heroic or Yarn-Teller Characters, in T13 they can create and collaborate to create stories and usually portray NPCs beyond their own character, as long as this does not affect another’s storyline or immersion (voting may be used to bypass Yarn-Telling Ordeals).'),
        // array('Type'=>'Immersive', 'Description'=>'Emerging in the 1990s and combining aspects of LARP and larp into table-top roleplaying created a new style of table-top play that emphasised player immersion in the game. This creates a wave of narrative and character-driven games that emphasise story-line, player narration and roleplaying, and moves away from simulationist play further. Rules are designed to be narrative led and simple, to increase player immersion. Some immersive games favour a strong Referee-led story, others are run without a Referee at all.', 'Rules'=>'Less simulationist rules are used. Yarn-Teller characters are encouraged along with Heroes. Rules that break player immersion (often on a case by case basis) are removed, simplified or replaced. Referees may take a back seat to Yarn-Teller led stories.'),
        // array('Type'=>'Ludonarrativist', 'Description'=>'The Ludonarrativist games emerge from the small-press games (and niche games) of the late 80s, were reformed and popularised initially by White Wolf’s Story-Teller games, and later evolved through sites like the Forge into ever more niche systems. These games try to increase immersion by minimising ludonarrative dissonance, combining detailed simulationist settings with abstracted gaming mechanics and story-led experiences, they achieve this by making the system, setting, and character objectives align and work together (results are, of course, entirely subjective). This created a swathe of games that have unique focuses, with game mechanics that emphasise a particular play style, atmosphere and feel of the game.', 'Rules'=>'T13 is designed with Ludonarrativist ideals and a genre-mashing omniversal setting to allow generic ludonarrative coherence. Of course, some Ludonarrativist games will require additional mechanics or changes in nomenclature, for example a Norse setting practically requires the Wyrd Tarot and/or Yarn-cards be at least referred to as Runes, a game about expert gamblers may implement a rule that the dice rolled only count if they fall within a given circle on the table, dice beyond the circle may count against the roll, might cost Sway to negate, or may add to the Drama Pool as required.'),
        // array('Type'=>'OSR', 'Description'=>'Despite the name the Old School Renaissance or Revival is a relatively new style of play that is somewhat reacting against Ludonarrativist play. The exact nature of this reaction can vary between groups, but commonly these can be explained by emphasising role-playing over mechanics, player skill over character skills, and one-off situational rulings over game rules. Generally the feeling in OSR seems to be that rules should be simple, easy and ignorable when appropriate. This is perhaps exemplified with the idea that dice rolls do not add flavour. If a battle is taking place on a cliff edge and the rules make no mention of push-back it makes no sense that the PCs or NPCs cannot fall from the cliff, instead an OSR Referee could decide any fumble or critical will result in a vertical excursion.', 'Rules'=>'OSR games can be run in T13, just remember that OSR has little use for complex or fiddly Rules (stick to simple Dice Pool play). Game flow and spontaneity are considered more important. OSR play favours play as Extras and Grunts.'),
        array(
            'Type' => 'Narrative',
            'Description' => 'Narrative play emphasises the story over everything else. Characters are defined mostly by their personal story-arcs, especially their backstory, and their effect on other stories. Challenges are generally narrative in nature. Characters are expected to fail before they learn to succeed.',
            'Rules' => 'Story beats Rules generally in Narrative play.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Character',
            'Description' => 'Character play emphasises the characters over everything else. Player’s are expected to remain in character, even during narration. Plot’s and Stories are generally Character Arcs or are generated by Character Yarn-Tellers. Challenges are generally Character challenges such as overcoming Hitches.',
            'Rules' => 'Character beats Rules in Character play. In Character based play it is usual to not use Extras for NPCs instead using at least Archetype NPCs or Lite Characters.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Realistic',
            'Description' => 'Realistic play emphasises realism over everything else. Characters are grounded. Challenges are usually everyday, emotional situations, or seem impossible. ',
            'Rules' => ''
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => '',
            'Description' => '',
            'Rules' => ''
        ) ,

    );
    public static $plotTypes = array(
        array(
            'Type' => 'Background',
            'Description' => 'Background plots are usually used as part of a World-building Game. They describe the major events, places and people in the universe, usually these are events that Characters cannot hope to have an impact upon either because of their size, the fact that the event has already happened, or never happened, but most people think it did anyway.',
            'Rules' => 'Background plots consist of Setting details (such as Locations, Characters, Descendants, Annexes and Proficiencies) and Events that have already happened (they may only be played through in Time travel Stories where they behave more like Destiny Plots). Generally Background Plots are unaffected by even the presence of Time-travellers, and "history" repairs itself often by the action of some agency such as the Paradox Warriors (or Chronomasters, Doomeisters, Special Committee for Aoristic Management, Parliament of Time, Council of Chronos, Labyrinthine Bulmäs, Eternals, etc. as appropriate to the setting) or the sheer bloody-mindedness of official historians. Background plots do not require Conflicts or Embodiments to be defined.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Character',
            'Description' => 'Character Plots focus on a Character and follow their Arc, the journey the Character takes from Grunt to wherever they are going. Often Character Plots are about overcoming or resolving a Hitch or some other problem in the Character’s life. This can often play out exactly like  an internal Conflict Plot.',
            'Rules' => 'Character Plots generally focus on a single Character, showing the changes to that Character that occur over time. They are often developed by Yarn-Tellers about their own Characters, or by Referees to bring Grunt Characters towards Hero or Yarn-Teller play. Character plots always have a Conflict and usually have at least one Dominant Side Hidden Embodiment (and always have at least one Hidden Embodiment and One Push or Pull Embodiment on another side) and ideally Embodies the entire (usually Internalised or Simple) Conflict within a single Character.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Conflict',
            'Description' => 'Most T13 Plots are Conflict plots. They examine a Conflict, through relationships of Hooked Embodiments (most importantly the Characters). Usually these Characters fight or compete over something, often one or more of the Dominant Side’s Embodiments has Monster Facets (although this is not common in Sports stories for example).',
            'Rules' => 'Conflict Plots must specify the Conflict and the Embodiments that have been Hooked, usually at least one PC is Hooked to the Conflict (although not necessarily). These Plots need not include actual Combat (Rational Conflicts), but do usually involve direct confrontation and competition if they don’t.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Core',
            'Description' => 'This is a Core Plot. Core components cannot be modified, but you can use them in your own projects. The Core Plots in T13 define the nature of the Omniverse, and can be found in novelised form in the "Paradox War" Trilogy.',
            'Rules' => 'Core plots are overarching themes in the system. They support other forms of play, and help to define common aspects across time and universes. Core Plots do not require Conflicts or Embodiments, but may have them in some cases. They are somewhat like "Super"-Background Plots, creating Multiverses that share similar rules.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Creation',
            'Description' => 'Creation Plots are a subset of Conflict Plots that try to create a specific Annex (usually reconciling the Conflict Proficiencies into the Annex). Creation Plots do not care if the Annex is created in Character or Descendant (although they usually favour Descendants).',
            'Rules' => 'Creation plots always specify the Annex that will be created, in addition to the Conflict and Hooked Characters. The Conflict must include Proficiency and/or Annex Embodiments from at least two sides (that will be combined to create the new Annex). Creation Conflicts are often Simple during early game, but later rise to even Exceptional Complexity.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Descendant',
            'Description' => 'Descendant Plots occur when a Plot is focused on a particular Descendant. These Descendants are often McGuffins that serve no real purpose beyond a plot device (they are often a Treasure), but they may be have Edges and Glows that grant them, or their owners, abilities.',
            'Rules' => 'Descendant Plots usually detail the Descendant to a fine degree, for example, that One Ring, grants invisibility from every eye, but the almost omniscient Villain, which is drawn to view anyone wearing it, and that one Sword will keep it’s wielder alive, almost no matter what, but drains the souls of anyone close to the wielder to do that. Sometimes, this alone can be enough to drive the Plot, but usually there is also at least one Opposed group or Character that will stop at nothing to get their hands on the Descendant. The Conflict must include at least one External Location or Descendant Embodiment, usually on the Dominant side (although not always).'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Destiny',
            'Description' => 'Destiny Plots usually are the result of in-game Prophecy and future Chronoliths. Destiny Plots should always foreshadowed in earlier Plots. If a Ref ever makes a reference to a future event, you can be sure there is a Destiny Plot brewing.',
            'Rules' => 'Destiny Plots include events that have not happened yet (and may not happen at all). The Plot will attempt to create the Event and have it happen as predicted, although other forces may be working against this Destiny. They are at their most obvious during time-travel Stories, where the expected future is some Characters’ pasts, if the "Future" events are changed, then the history of some Characters, and even the setting may be altered. Destiny Plots do not require Conflicts, and when they do, they are often Simple or Internalised, they are rarely Balanced or bigger.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Geo-plot',
            'Description' => 'Geo-plots are Plots that have possessed or become fossilised in a Location. They are common to Old School Games. The Size of the Location is usually related to the Size of the Plot.',
            'Rules' => 'GeoPlots always require a Map of the Location, this Map usually includes sub-Locations (such as rooms in the Dungeon) which will have associated Events (such as Warps and Wefts) that will occur when the room is entered. Geo-plots usually present fossilised Conflicts from years ago, such as ancient castles that were built for forgotten wars, but will contain more recent echoes of these plots in the activities of the Characters (they seek an ancient weapon from the Forgotten Wars to defeat the Lich-King). Geo-plots are often quite static, with events in one room of the dungeon, or kingdom having little impact on events in other rooms, or countries, but this will vary with the Yarn-Teller, and the nature of the Geo-plot.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Hitch',
            'Description' => 'Hitch Plots try to spread a particular Hitch to as many Characters as possible. They represent things like Plagues, or Crime-waves... Sometimes this Hitch will be happy to spread as a quirk, other times the Hitch will only be happy when everyone is infected with a Woe (although there will probably be an Increated by such determined Hitch Plots).',
            'Rules' => 'Hitch Plots have to have some specification of the Hitch that will be spread (what exactly is the plague and what does it do to people who are infected), they usually have some victory conditions set (such as infecting more than 80% of the population of a certain Location to Flaw level or better), as well as a Failure condition (such as more than 20% of the population being vaccinated - or evacuated). Hitch Plots always have a Conflict with at least one Hitch Embodiment.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Political',
            'Description' => 'Political Plots are based around Conflicts within a Pact Descendant (see Social). Unlike a Social Plot, in Politics there is more emphasis on competition and Conflict (although rarely Rational Conflict) with some out group.',
            'Rules' => 'Political Plots must be at least Balanced in size and include a Pact Descendant (usually on the Pressed or Below Side). They are always more complex than they first appear, and while they rarely include direct conflict between the Sides, they do spawn sub-Plots that may (and usually do) include Rational Conflict (and sometimes even Monsters).'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Quest',
            'Description' => 'Quest Plots are based around a specific Quest, made so large that a whole Plot is required to handle it. Quest Plots are often tied to specific Descendants or Characters and usually set Stories rather than Test or Ordeals for the Quest-lines.',
            'Rules' => 'Quest Plots are based around a single Quest, although Quests usually have additional details that require specification, for example, when the Quest is to defend a Location from attack, the Quest Plot must specify the Location (detail the Location that requires protecting), and specify the forces attempting to attack (such as a single Monster or Pact Descendant "Army" for example). Quest Plots usually have a Conflict, often a Simple one (although not necessarily), but have at least one External Quest Embodiment that will share its Hexagram with the Plot.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Relationship',
            'Description' => 'Relationship Plots are "Tension" driven plots between two or more Characters. Romance and Buddy Plots are subsets of the Relationship Plot. They are about interactions between characters, trust, friendship, love, as often as mistrust, enmity and hate.',
            'Rules' => 'Relationship Plots must have Conflicts that have at least two sides of the Conflict with Pulled Embodiments. Whoever is Hooked by this Plot in those Pulled Embodiments, will be drawn into a Relationship by the Plot. Relationship plots are usually Soul Stakes in the Zenith.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Social',
            'Description' => 'Social Plots are plots about whole communities, usually a Pact-Descendant. Usually the whole Conflict is Embodied within members of that community (and External Embodiments), apart from the External side. Often Social Plots Sides will Embody Internally as other Pacts within the larger Pact, for example, within a Social Plot set in a High School the Sides could Embody as the Faculty or as the cliques among the students.',
            'Rules' => 'The Conflict must include at least one Pact Descendant Embodiment (and usually more than one in the form of Internalised Conflicts).'
        ) ,
    );
