<text x="28.764971" y="40.711075" fill="#000000" font-family="sans-serif" font-size="10.583px" stroke-width=".26458" style="line-height:1.25" xml:space="preserve"><tspan x="28.764971" y="40.711075"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="53.940201"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="67.169327"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="80.398445"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="93.627571"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="106.8567"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="120.08582"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="133.31494"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="146.54407"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="159.77319"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="173.00232"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="186.23145"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="199.46057"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="212.6897"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="225.91882"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="239.14795"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="252.37708"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="265.6062"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="278.83533"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="292.06445"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="305.29358"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="318.52271"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="331.7518"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="344.98093"/><tspan x="28.764971" y="358.21005"/></text>
<g>
	<g>
		<rect x="16.078" y="36.701" width="76.028" height="76.028" fill="#848481" stroke="#000704" stroke-width=".565"/>
		<path d="m18.377 52.549c73.559-0.31728 73.559-0.15865 73.559-0.15865" fill="none" marker-end="url(#d)" marker-start="url(#c)" stroke="#f30000" stroke-width=".39803"/>
		<text transform="scale(.87999 1.1364)" x="68.705223" y="45.620499" fill="#000000" font-family="sans-serif" font-size="4.3754px" stroke="#f30000" stroke-width=".1" style="line-height:1.25" xml:space="preserve"><tspan x="68.705223" y="45.620499" stroke="#f30000" stroke-width=".1">1.5m</tspan></text>
		<path d="m17.811 37.933 73.734 73.892" fill="none" marker-end="url(#b)" marker-start="url(#a)" stroke="#009ef8" stroke-width=".7741"/>
	</g>
	<text transform="matrix(.61341 .60448 -.81503 .82707 0 0)" x="89.791252" y="11.285429" fill="#000000" font-family="sans-serif" font-size="4.64px" stroke="#009ef8" stroke-width=".116" style="line-height:1.25" xml:space="preserve"><tspan x="89.791252" y="11.285429" stroke="#009ef8" stroke-width=".116">2m</tspan></text>
</g>
</svg></figure><p>The normal scale used in RPGs is usually 25-32mm figurines, which is around 1:56 to 1:64 scale. At this Scale a 1 inch square on the battle board represents about 5 foot square in the game-world (although these are rarely accurately scaled).</p><p>In T13, we use metres not feet for range and movement calculations so keeping the standard scale, standard squares are treated as being 1.5 metres across, their diagonal length is very close to 2 metres. Motion across these squares can be measured 2 full squares being 3 metres across, or moving diagonally will count as 2 metres, although the types of motion used will determine the card Pips required for these motions.</p>'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Simulation',
            'Description' => 'The area is mapped, or modelled accurately, but not marked with squares or similar nonsense. Instead the scale is considered accurate and is marked upon the map, and is a consistent scale with miniatures. Indicating the length of 1 metre (or 10 kilometres, or whatever the appropriate scale of the map). Positions of Characters are marked with miniatures, figurines or markers that are moved around the map.',
            'Rule' => 'Based on the scale of the map all Ranges and distances are calculated with a rule. For example, if the map is built on a scale of 1 inch = 100 km and you measure a distance of 8.4 inches then the range would be 840 km. This is the most simulationist model that is available, and may include optional rules such as penalties for soft, muddy, loose ground, pushing through deep vegetation, bushes, nettles, and thorns.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Psychosocial',
            'Description' => 'The Ordeal takes place in a non-physical environment, like a Character’s mindscape, a dreamscape, or the interconnected emotional states of a group or community. Psychosocial Action Spaces are best described as a combination of a Shot-Zones, Venn diagrams and a Node-Map. Although the most simple Psychosocial Spaces are typically grid-like arrangements. Psychosocial spaces vary greatly depending upon what is being modelled. Psychosocial Spaces are controlled by the Eidolon, the genius Loci of the space, which may be the Character themselves, or some other monster of the Id.',
            'Rule' => '<ul><li>Psychosocial Action Spaces consist of Spaces (that can be any shape, but often reflect the Geometry of the Character). These Spaces can be used to indicate any Psychosocial ideation or collection that is required in the model: they may represent <ul><li>Characters</li><li>Social groups</li><li>Psychosocial Spaces</li><li>Individual emotions</li></ul></li><li>Like a Venn diagram, Psychosocial Spaces can overlap, with the over-lapping borders creating additional spaces that fall within multiple spaces simultaneously, such that a Character placed there would experience all possible influences. These may be influences such as <ul><li>emotional states</li><li>membership of a group</li><li>Or other proximity of philosophy, religious, scientific thought, etc. or any other psychosocial entities</li></ul></li><li>Spaces may have have marked and labelled centres, which may be connected like a node map. These connections can vary what they are indicating, depending upon the space being modelled:<ul><li>Lines of communication (usually between Characters or Pacts) although Drives in Private Psychosocial Spaces apply</li><li>Relative levels of hostility between characters</li><li>Neurological, Memetic, Philosophical, Scientific, folkloric or magical connections (such as magical  correspondences).</li></ul><li>Characters may move within the Psychosocial Action Space, by paying a Difficulty in a certain type of Sway, Score or Suited Pips as the Yarn-Teller, Referee or Author requires (Difficulties are typically calculated in Pips). [t13ne type="displaytable" array="PsychosocialDifficulties" /]</li></li></ul><figure><figcaption>An example Social Map that depicts 9 Characters forming two groups.</figcaption><?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
