    public static $nightmareZones = array(
        array(
            'Nightmare_Points' => 0,
            'Type' => 'Relieved',
            'Description' => 'This Nightmare Zone still holds some disturbances and disturbing imagery, but has largely returned to a normal part of the Dreamspace.',
            'Rules' => 'This is what happens to a Nightmare Zone that has all of the Nightmare Points removed, drained or the Trauma is healed.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Nightmare_Points' => 1,
            'Type' => 'Disturbing',
            'Description' => 'This Nightmare Zone contains a disturbing dream aspect. Dream aspects could include sounds, imagery, dream Extras, conversation topics, dream locations, odd dream logic, as well as Obstacles in the Dreeamscape. The disturbing nature of the aspects are often related to the initial Trauma that created the Nightmare Zone, although blood, sex, death and violence feature commonly.',
            'Rules' => 'A single Nightmare point creates a circular Nightmare Zone within the Dreamscape. If the sleeper enters the Nightmare Zone during a dream they will Gain Stress.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Nightmare_Points' => 2,
            'Type' => 'Distressing',
            'Description' => 'This Nightmare Zone contains multiple disturbing aspects, which mingle and mix in the Dreamspace to create a Distressing dream. Usually a distressing Dream will include multiple distrubing noises and imagery as well as Nightmare Characters.',
            'Rules' => 'Two Nightmare points creates a Nightmare Path, which connects two circular zones to create a straight line path in the Dreamscape. Nightmare Paths may create Monsters with upto 2 Monster Facets. Nightmare Paths can create 1 card negative Psych effects on the sleeper that may linger upon awakening, often a Path will make multiple attempts at this until it succeeds. If the sleeper enters the path, they must travel it to either end, be emotionally affected, and Gain Stress twice, once to enter and once to escape again.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Nightmare_Points' => 3,
            'Type' => 'Fitful',
            'Description' => 'This Nightmare Zone contains a fitful dream. Fitful dreams are made from multiple disturbing aspects, tied together with a disturbing story, and cause the sleeper to twitch and moan in their sleep. Fitful dreams are often extremely distressing and disturbing, but are not quite enough to force the sleeper to wake up. Instead, the sleeper may move or wordlessly sleep-talk, acting out the dream.',
            'Rules' => 'Three Nightmare Points creates a Nightmare Triangle, which will hold a full dream narrative, often with seemingly branching events, like an Ordeal or Plot. Nightmare Triangles can create Monsters (with to upto 3 Monster Facets) and 2 Card Negative Psych Effects on the Sleeper (which they may try multiple times with Psych Attacks, until one sticks). Entering the Nightmare Triangle will cause a sleeper to Gain Stress three times before they can exit the Triangle.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Nightmare_Points' => 4,
            'Type' => 'Nightmare',
            'Description' => 'This Nightmare Zone is the first to truly be worthy of the name Nightmare. These are the dreams so bad that Characters awaken screaming in the dark, and must immediately turn on the lights.',
            'Rules' => 'Four Nightmare points creates a Nightmare Plane, a rectangular area in the Character’s Dreamscape. The Nightmare Plane contains many disturbing Characters, Locations and events, which can be connected by a narrative, but more often shift randomly. The Nightmare Plane will create a 3 Card Psych Emotional Effect on the sleeper and can create Monsters with upto 4 Monster Facets. Exiting the Nightmare Plane is impossible without Gaining Stress 4 times, and then the sleeper awakens often screaming or crying out (exhibiting the 3 card Psych effect), and if they try to sleep again too quickly (typically at least twenty minutes to an hour must be spent awake, and the emotional effect recovered from or replaced with a positive emotional effect) or they will enter the Nightmare Plane again.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Nightmare_Points' => 5,
            'Type' => 'Parasomnia',
            'Description' => 'This Nightmare Zone casts out the normal rules of sleep. Letting the sleeper completely act out their nightmares, screaming, sleep-talking, sleep-walking, as well as occasionally attacking those who try to restrain or wake them, although these are more often defensive actions. Parasomnia can even cause Nightmares to spread, with screams and whispered horrors from one sleeper disturbing the dreams of other sleepers nearby.',
            'Rules' => 'Five Nightmare points creates a Nightmare Star. A Nightmare Star extends beyond the Dreamscape of a single Character in five directions (the pentagon is held within the Dreamscape, the pentagram arms extend beyond into other parts of the Psychosocial space). The Nightmare Star can create Extreme 3 Card Psych Effects, that the sleeper must suffer through to awaken. The Nightmare Star can contain Monster(IV) Characters (who need not be Extras and can be potential Alts or exterior beings depending upon genre) with upto 4 Monster Facets. Depending upon the Psychosocial spaces touched by the Nightmare Star a Character may speak, act out the dream, or the Nightmare can also create Nightmare Points in another Character who is sleeping nearby, as their Dreams become affected. It is possible for a Nightmare Point to move permanently from one sleeper to another in this way, but should not happen easily. Sleepers entering the Nightmare Star  must Gain Stress 5 times to awaken from the nightmare themselves (otherwise they will walk around acting the dream out until someone else awakens them). Although they may Relieve Stress for each other Character’s sleep they disturb or awaken.'
        ) ,
    );
    public static $psychologicalDefences = array(
        array(
            'Type' => 'Acting out',
            'Description' => 'Acting out is when a Character acts in response to an unconscious wish or emotion that they are not even aware of.',
            'Rules' => 'Acting out works as a Prepared Psych Defence with the Character’s Acting Out Action also preparing the Defence. In a Psychosocial space this will create a barrier or Obstacle as a result of the Action.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Avoidance',
            'Description' => 'Avoidance is a very primitive psychological defence mechanism. If something, or someone, has hurt you in the past, then if you avoid them for the rest of your life they cannot do it to you again.',
            'Rules' => 'Avoidance is pretty much trying to use a Dodge action to avoid Psych damage, but if you are in the same Location as the person, or thing, you are trying to avoid then the defence has already failed. Avoidance usually involves not going to places their abuser goes or even knows. '
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Denial',
            'Description' => 'Whatever is happening (or happened) the Character will deny it, essentially lying to themselves, as well as others.',
            'Rules' => 'Denial works as an Ignore Active Psych Defence to mitigate harm. Within the Psychosocial space Denial often appears as a blackness, smoke, fog, or veil that covers and hides whatever is being denied.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Displacement',
            'Description' => 'Displacement is about shifting the target or goal to avoid something dangerous or (usually socially) unacceptable. Typically negative emotions connected with one target are moved to another. Positive Emotions can be Displaced too if there is psychological need.',
            'Rules' => 'Displacement works as a Focus Active Psych Defence, however any Emotional Effect during the attack is postponed until after the Character has been alone and then encounters another (third) Character. The emotional effect will then apply as though this third Character had made the attack. In Psychosocial spaces Displacement can also create tunnels within the space that act as portals to displace a concept (or Thread) within the space.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Dissociation',
            'Description' => 'Dissociation is a drastic modification of personality in order to avoid emotional trauma. Dissociation can create Alternate Personalities (or reveal them at least).',
            'Rules' => 'Dissociation typically involves a Character shutting down all access to a Facet in order to not feel the emotions of that Facet. This can be performed by any Character who is affected by 3 (or more) cards of emotions simultaneously (this might be 3 different emotions, two 2 card emotions or a single 3 card emotion). The Character can decide to Dissociate one or more emotion card. Dissociation is temporary solution, however as this state causes the Character to Gain Stress equal to the Chi Extend Duration for each Dissociated Card present. Dissociation can sometimes manifest as a different Persona or Core if the original Persona or Core Facet is shutdown, and if the "Dissociated Personality" is given a different name (perhaps a nickname) a differernt Geometry can emerge also. If Stress related Trauma occurs while Dissociated a new Alt may be created instead. Dissociation "removes" the emotions that are currently being felt from the Psychosocial space using the Dissociated cards as an Obstacle to accessing that emotional State, the cards also limit access to the Facet (adding the Obstacle Difficulty to all actions with the Facet) and any Proficiencies or Annexes that rely on it.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Distortion',
            'Description' => 'Why accept the truth when instead you can reshape reality to meet your emotional needs? This is a form of denial, where the denier reinterprets evidence in a more positive light for themselves.',
            'Rules' => 'Distortion works as an Ignore Active Psych Defence. Within a Psychosocial space Distortion will alter the appearance of anything within the space as required, however these Distorted images can be noticed as not quite being normal, this does not allow the original to be recovered, it at best reveals that what is there is false. However, if a foundational Distortion can be broken, overwhelmed, and proved to be false, then all Distortions may collapse and reveal the true Psychosocial space.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Frenzy',
            'Description' => 'Frenzy is a specific Hysteria/Sublimation that converts any emotional situation into blind rage. This is a very negative emotional defence, that converts any emotional state into very negative emotions.',
            'Rules' => 'Frenzy works as a negative Sublimation, converting any stressful emotional state into Rage, with the Stress being spent on Straining any Annex Attack Actions on any available target. The Frenzy will not end until all the Stress has been spent. In a Psychosocial space a Frenzy usually appears as a Force-Of-Nature Extra, which can express as an animal, beast, monster, storm, flood, landslide, or whatever takes the Yarn-Teller’s imagination.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Hysteria',
            'Description' => 'Hysteria (or more correctly Pathological Conversion) is when an intrapsychic conflict is expressed through a physical symptom. Examples include hysterical blindness, deafness, numbness (emotional or physical) or any one of a number of other ailments and afflictions.',
            'Rules' => 'Rather than taking emotional affects (and potentially Traumas) the Character elects instead to activate their Hysteria Defence. The Pips of the emotional attack are Reduced, and become the Banes of a Temporary Hitch (often a Loss of Sense, Lacking or Bound Hitch). The Pips of the original attack indicate the Chi Extend Duration of the Hysterical Hitch. In the Psychosocial space, Hysteria often appears as an Extra, who may be aggressive, protective, duplicitous, blunt or persuasive as the Yarn-Teller prefers, but they take this sense or deny it to the Character to protect them from something (which may or may not be real too).'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Monstrous',
            'Description' => 'Monstrous is a Sublimation that causes a Character unleash their inner monster to protect themselves from harm. This is often the case with demonic possessions and the like where the possessee will give over control to the demon for protection.',
            'Rules' => 'Monstrous functions either as Frenzy and Sublimation, moving Stress to a Monster Facet (typically their Persona or Core Facet becomes the Monster Facet), or as Regression / Dissociation if a suitable Alt is available. In the Psychosocial space Monstrous defences will create a Monster, usually a Force-Of-Nature Extra with Monster Facets. This Monster will attempt to protect the mind, and particularly Ego, from any issues arising from the outside world. The Monster will from time to time seize control of an area of the Psychosocial landscape, often the consciousness, as they take control of the physical body and mind. Depending upon Genre and setting the Monster may be able to manifest independently in and affect only Psychosocial and / or real Action Spaces as required.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Passive-Aggression',
            'Description' => 'Indirect hostility is a result of repressing negative emotions against a person. As a defence it works best against a single target, often someone who asks a thing be done that the passive-aggressor will agree to do, but then not follow through.',
            'Rules' => 'Passive-Aggression works as a Focus Active Psych Defence against only one individual at once. In Psychosocial space Passive-Aggression usually expresses as an Extra who is the cause of the negative emotions, this Character will often be disguised (often as a Monster of some sort), usually as a distortion of who they really represent. A Passive-Aggressive response to a bad boss, may create a monster that represents all the negative emotions associated with the boss and it is this "dragon" that begins to behave as an Alt trying to express these negative emotions in indirect ways, such as opposing, resenting, griping, using sarcasm, and complaining about anything they are asked to do by anyone else.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Posturing',
            'Description' => 'Posturing is a basic defence mechanism that relies on not showing that you have been affected by an emotional attack. When scared, for example, one may posture bravado.',
            'Rules' => 'Posturing works as a Focus Active Psych Defence. Within the Psychosocial space Posturing is often expressed as statues (which may be Obstacles), or occasionally Extras. As long as the Posture is maintained the emotion is suppressed and ignored.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Projection',
            'Description' => 'Redirects negative self-thought, feelings, and failings onto others. Technically this is a Displacement of attribution, where the negative thoughts one feels are attributed to another, but it occurs often enough in isolation to be its own defence.',
            'Rules' => 'Projection works as an Ignore Active Psych Defence. Within a Psychosocial space the Projection will often appear as mirror, or water, a reflective surface, sometimes this will create a knight in shining armour Extra who will strike down the negative thoughts as being from outside. Other times the projection will instead "other" internal unwanted thoughts, making them appear as suddenly exotic, alien or terrifying.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Rationalization',
            'Description' => 'A Character will rationalise that whatever is happening must be their own fault, or it is happening to them for a reason.',
            'Rules' => 'Rationalization works as a Focus Active Psych Defence. In a Psychosocial space Rationalization will often take the form of "Justifiers". Justifiers are Extras that roam the Psychosocial area finding ways to justify the Character assuming blame for everything, sometimes they appear as authority figures to the Character, such as school teachers, police, judges, priests, politicians, gods, or parental figures. The justifiers can end up appearing as Split Alts taking control to assume blame for the Character.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Reaction Formation',
            'Description' => 'A Character take a stance opposite to that they truly believe and feel to be true, in order to deflect, displace, and hide their true self from harm. It may be this mechanism that leads to latent homosexuality expressing as homophobia in some cases.',
            'Rules' => 'Reaction Formation works as a Focus Active Psych Defence. Within a Psychosocial space a Reaction Formation will often appear as both a barrier or Obstacle around the true feelings, and a number of Extras will roam the space loudly expressing an opposed, or distracting, opinion. The Extras will always act to stop any Character from entering that area along with the Obstacle. If a Reaction Formation is particularly old and strongly embedded then there may be Ordeal levels of layers of Obstacles envisioned as a vault, fortress, tower or dungeon keeping the truth prisoner.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Reflection',
            'Description' => 'Reflection is a defence mechanism that can works (when it works) by making the target think that the Character is more like them, building sympathy between the Characters, or at least mutual fear, and making an attack less likely. In some ways Reflection is perhaps a variation on Passive-Aggression',
            'Rules' => 'Reflection works as an Ignore Active Psych Defence, however the Character must attempt to replicate the attack back as their next Action, which will effectively counter it. Within the Psychosocial space you will find internal Extras who represent aspects of the target being reflected, they represent what the Character who owns the space thinks and feels about the reflected target, especially what they admire or fear about them will be exaggerated (often via fantasy, superhero or horror tropes, depending upon the interests of the Character) in the Extras. '
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Regression',
            'Description' => 'Regression is a neurotic defence mechanism that causes the Character to abandon more mature Psych Defences to fall back on ones that worked for the Character when they were younger. Typically this results in whining, temper tantrums, and other childish behaviour.',
            'Rules' => 'Regression creates a "Regressed" Subsumed Same Personality Disorder Alt (note that Personality Disorder Alts should be used with care), that takes whatever emotional effects, trauma or mental damage that the Character wishes to not take on their original Alt. With time the Alt may diverge more and begin to fight for dominance with the original personality creating a Split or Unstable Integration.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Repression',
            'Description' => 'Repression tries to ensure that anything that would Stress the conscious mind is hidden from the conscious mind. Repressed memories and emotions have a habit of escaping though, emerging in the Dreamscape or Supernature (or elsewhere) as nightmares, sleepwalking, poltergeists, or related activity.',
            'Rules' => 'Repression can be used by a Character who has taken a Negative Emotion for any reason. That Emotion (and usually any memories associated  with this event) are Repressed, removed from the conscious mind of the Character to their unconscious mind. The Emotion and memory are typically moved in the Psychosocial space of the Character to their Mental Defences, however each card and memory in that Space will cause the Character to Gain 1 Stress every day it remains there. Emotions can be moved back, or into another Pscyhosocial space for no cost, but they can only move along a line or cross a line as the Character wakes or falls asleep.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Sublimation',
            'Description' => 'Sublimation is converting typically unhealthy emotions and behaviours into healthy actions, behaviours and emotions. This may allow artists to turn suffering into better art, or sports-people to place emotional content in their actions. Sublimation can be inverted though, and a Frenzy represents a similar but inverted defence.',
            'Rules' => 'Sublimation allows a Character to remove any Negative Emotion by converting the Pips of Negative Emotion into Stress placing it on at least one of their Annexes and immediately Straining those Annexes to spend that Stress. Within the Psychosocial space Sublimation often appears as internal Extras that have chimerical natures. The chimerical form often represents the emotion or behaviour being sublimated into an action or feeling, so we might see a dragon, bear or lion form that has been fused with an athelete, signifying predatory thoughts or negative emotions sublimated into sports performance.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Suppression',
            'Description' => 'Suppression is the defence mechanism of immediately squashing <em><strong>all</strong></em> emotional reactions until they can be dealt with in a more safe space later. Suppression can in some cases be similar to an overload burning-out a circuit, where an intense emotion can seem to burn out all emotional responses, at least for a while making the Character seem almost robotic or disconnected in nature',
            'Rules' => 'Suppression works by defering a specific emotional affect for a duration equal to the Pips of the attacks as a Limit Duration. Within a Psychosocial space suppression can appear in a number of ways, from a fire truck turning up to douse flames of rage, or a librarian that deafens the area shushing any discussion on a topic. No emotional cards may have any effect until the Suppression is over, with emotions and their effects paused.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Working Through',
            'Description' => 'Working Through is technically not a defence, but is instead about expressing and working through powerful emotions with as little long term damage as possible. Working Through is more about coping with and minimising emotional damage than stopping it.',
            'Rules' => 'Working Through does not strictly act as a defence, but instead allows large emotional effects to be broken apart into smaller less dangerous effects, before they are allowed to damage the Character. An emotional effect can be broken apart into its component 1 card effects, however the Character will also gain Stress equal to the largest single card Pips in the effect, and have to deal with the individual effects and their damage separately.'
        ) ,
    );

    public static $woundFreshType = array(
        array(
            'Icon' => '🍒',
            'Name' => 'Fresh',
            'Description' => 'When a Wound is so fresh you are still holding the card.',
            'Rules' => 'When you reach the end of the Round, note the Suit and Pips of the Wound as appropriate (next to a Proficiency / Annex Slot or Hitch) and Discard the card, this Wound is now Untreated ⏱️. Hitch causing Mortal+ Wounds will increase the Hitch at the end of the next Round again.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Icon' => '⏱️',
            'Name' => 'Untreated',
            'Description' => 'Any Wound on the Character or Descendant that has been there for a little while.',
            'Rules' => 'Untreated Wounds linger doing their thing. Depending on the situation Untreated Wounds will begin to Fester after a few minutes / hours / days. Untreated Wounds create an Unsoakable Distract on the Character or Descendant every time they act.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Icon' => '🤒',
            'Name' => 'Treated',
            'Description' => 'This Wound has been cleaned and sealed, by medicine, therapy, magic, surgery, or first-aid.',
            'Rules' => 'A Treated Wound can be thought of as behaving like a -1 Level Wound, so a Crippling Wound behaves like a Maiming Wound. Hitches will no longer increase automatically in Mortal+ Wounds. Treated Wounds can be re-opened by any Flesh Wound, but with time will Stabilize.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Icon' => '🤕',
            'Name' => 'Stabilized',
            'Description' => 'This Wound begun naturally or narratively healing, the wound may have bled and clotted, or the bones may have begun to repair, the fever has broken, or the nightmares are no longer every night.',
            'Rules' => 'A Stabilized Wound is a Wound on pause. It no longer has its active effect, but still isn\'t fully healed yet. Any Action that "breaks" the Wound, such as using a Crippled Annex, or Maimed Proficiency, or triggering the Hitch of a Stabilized Mortal Wound will create Stress equal to the Wound Pips. Any Action that creates Shock or any fresh Flesh Wound will re-open the Wound. '
        ) ,
        array(
            'Icon' => '🎃',
            'Name' => 'Re-opened',
            'Description' => 'When you stretch a wound and it starts bleeding again, it’s re-opened.',
            'Rules' => 'Re-opened Wounds go back to being active, Maims block Proficiencies, Crippling block Annexes and Mortal+ Wounds go back to increasing Hitches. Re-opened Wounds cause an Unsoakable Distract whenever the Character or Descendant acts.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Icon' => '☠️',
            'Name' => 'Festering',
            'Description' => 'Festering Wounds are untreated (or re-opened) Wounds that have gone bad, or have been poisoned by a Toxin. Sometimes specific attacks create Festering Wounds other times they have just been left too long (days normally, hours in a jungle, minutes in a sewer or based on the Toxin involved) without treatment.',
            'Rules' => 'Festering Wounds create an Unsoakable Flesh Wound (which will try to aggravate the original wound) every time the Character acts (performs a full or half-action). Kind Yarn-Tellers may allow half-actions to create an Unsoakable Distract instead.'
        )
    );
    public static $healingModes = array(
        array(
            'Name' => 'Chirurgery',
            'Icon' => '☤',
            'Description' => 'The forerunner of modern surgery and medicine, a combination of faith healing, herbalism, astrology, magic and surgical techniques (largely conducted without anaesthetics). As likely to kill as to cure.',
            'Rules' => '<strong>Chirurgery Ordeal</strong> — High Stakes<ul><li>Maximum Wound Level Healed equals Chirugeon’s Phoenix Facet Score (e.g. at Boon 13 up to Crippling).</li><li>May automatically Stabilize any wound with Pip Score lower than Half the Chirugeon’s Phoenix Boon</li><li>Beat total Pips of all Wounds with Hearts <span class="t13ne-redcard">&hearts;</span> (+2 Pips for Trump) or Suited cards and Heal the Level of the Wound by one (Mortal becomes Crippling). Failure to Heal all Wounds will aggravate all Wounds by one Level (Mortal becomes Carnage).</li><li>Halve Diff if all Wounds are Treated 🤒 or Stabilized 🤕 first.</li><li>Double Diff if any Wound is Festering ☠️.</li></ul>',
            'Applicable_Wounds' => '👤⚒⭐',
            'Best_Result' => '- 1 Level to all Wounds and wounds are "Treated".',
            'Worst_Result' => 'Aggravate all Wounds 1 Level. All Wounds now Fester if any Wound did.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Name' => 'First-Aid',
            'Icon' => '🚑',
            'Description' => 'The techniques of the Paramedic, these techniques are intended to keep someone from dying, or losing body-parts. First-aid is about stabilizing Wounds, so that surgeons, or medicines can treat them more easily. Although good first-aid practices will also encourage natural regeneration.',
            'Rules' => '<strong>First Aid</strong> — Takes place within a standard Ordeal (same Stakes as Ordeal). <ul><li>Match Suit (or use &hearts;) and match or beat Pips of each individual Wound.</li><li>Diff x2 if Reopened 🎃.</li><li>Diff x3 if Festering ☠️</li><li>Can only Treat a Wound</li></ul>',
            'Applicable_Wounds' => '⚡⚒',
            'Best_Result' => 'Treats Wound 🤒 (Halves Diff to Heal)',
            'Worst_Result' => 'Aggravate 1 Level.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Name' => 'Healing',
            'Icon' => '🙏',
            'Description' => 'Magic, Prayers, or super-technology can all be super effective at healing certain Wounds. Micro and Nano-surgery technology can reattach, or regrow limbs which would have been lost. Spells can reweave limbs and Prayers can even bring people back from the dead.',
            'Rules' => '<strong>Healing Ordeal</strong> — Soul stakes <ul><li>Beat total Pips of all current Wounds + Age of oldest Wound in Chi (Extend Duration) with Hearts <span class="t13ne-redcard">&hearts;</span>.</li><li>Ordeal is 3 Stages long, Preparation (<span class="t13ne-redcard">&diams;</span> Trump), Enchantment (<span class="t13ne-redcard">&hearts;</span> Trump), Cleansing (<span class="t13ne-redcard">&hearts;</span> Trump). Failure in any Stage results in complete failure.</li></ul> ',
            'Applicable_Wounds' => '👤⚡⚒⭐',
            'Best_Result' => 'Heals all Wounds completely removing them.',
            'Worst_Result' => 'Failure results in Yarn-Teller or Ref’s choice of: <ol><li>Wounds are duplicated to Healer</li><li>Healer is attacked by Psych or magical versions of the Wounds (but may Soak)</li><li>All Wounds Fester ☠️</li><li>All Wounds Re-open</li><li>No changes of any sort (are you sure? This one is really boring)</li><ol>'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Name' => 'Jury-rigging',
            'Icon' => '🔨',
            'Description' => 'Jury-rigging is a technique of repair where an attempt is made to negate a Wound for a while. It is rarely intended to be a permanent fix, but simply a quick-fix that can be later improved. Jury-rigging is usually intended for Descendants, but jury-rigging can be used to splint broken limbs, bind wounds, and clean wounds.',
            'Rules' => '<strong>Jury-rigging Test</strong> — Jury-rigging is about creating a fast and dirty quick fix.<ul><li>Match Suit (or <span class="t13ne-redcard">♥️</span>) and Beat the Pips of a Wound.</li><li>Difficulty is Pips for most Wounds.</li><li>Diff &times;2 for Festering Wounds</li><li>Success Stabilizes the Wound immediately for a period equal to the Pips beaten by as a Yarn Extend Duration after which the wound will immediately Fester ☠️. Failure will make the Wound Fester ☠️ automatically and apply a Fresh 🍒 copy of the original.</li></ul>',
            'Applicable_Wounds' => '⚡⚒',
            'Best_Result' => 'Stabilizes a Wound for a Yarn Extend Duration equal to the Pips over the Difficulty.',
            'Worst_Result' => 'Wound automatically Festers ☠️ and a Fresh 🍒 copy is applied.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Name' => 'Medicine',
            'Icon' => '🏥',
            'Description' => 'Potions, poultices, and pills that are scientifically proven to make money for doctors, pharmacists and drug companies. Not every cure works, and not every Wound type is treatable, depending on the time period. These are usually Descendants taken for a period of treatment, that may have side-effects (often quirk or Flaw Hitches) such as Consuming. Medicine can be as simple as chewing the right leaf, or wearing a sling for a day or it can involve weeks of expensive therapies.',
            'Rules' => '<strong>Medicine Ordeal</strong><ul><li>Beat a Wound’s Pips x2 with cards (match Suit or <span class="t13ne-redcard">&hearts;</span>).</li><li>Difficulty equals Pips if Stabilized🤕 or Treated 🤒</li><li>Pips x3 if Festering ☠️</li></ul>',
            'Applicable_Wounds' => '👤⚡⚒',
            'Best_Result' => 'Wound is Treated.',
            'Worst_Result' => 'Aggravate 1 Level.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Name' => 'Narrative Healing',
            'Icon' => '✒️',
            'Description' => 'Narrative Healing is the sort of healing that most people work on themselves during the story. Narrative Healing often represents wounds that initially look worse than they are, or at least hurt more, but that later are forgotten or shrugged off. Narrative Healing’s effectiveness varies with the Genre. In some, it hardly works at all, in others you can shrug off explosions (looking at you 80’s action movies and cartoons).',
            'Rules' => '<strong>Narrative Healing</strong> — Takes place during the Standard Ordeal (usually during the Fight)<br/>It may may only effect Fresh Wounds (that is Wounds that are still cards), so can only be used during the Round when the Wound was first applied. The Referee and Yarn-Teller decide the Maximum Narrative Healing Pips based on the Genre between 3 (for realistic) and 13 (for 80s Action movies and cartoons).<ul><li>Narrative Healing with a lower Wound card. The card must be within the Maximum Narrative Healing Pips of the Wound being healed, and be Suited or a Heart. E.g. If the Max Narrative Heal Pips are 8, a Joker (Pips 15) can be replaced with any card from a 7 to an Ace (14). This healing card replaces the original (potentially) Carnage+ Wound as a new Fresh Maiming, Crippling, Mortal or Carnage Wound, as appropriate.</li><li>Regardless of Genre a suited (or &hearts;) card of greater Pips than the Wound will Stabilize the Wound (Skipping Treated Wounds). For example, if you have a K <span class="t13ne-blackcard">&spades;</span> Mortal Wound, you may Narrative Heal with an Ace of <span class="t13ne-blackcard">&spades;</span> or <span class="t13ne-redcard">&hearts;</span> or the Q and K of <span class="t13ne-redcard">&hearts;</span> (due to the +2 Trump Pips) and Stabilize the Wound.</li></ul>',
            'Applicable_Wounds' => '👤⚡⚒⭐',
            'Best_Result' => 'Wound Stabilized / Wound replaced with lower Wound, wound remains Fresh',
            'Worst_Result' => 'Wound Unchanged'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Name' => 'Natural Regeneration',
            'Icon' => '🛏️',
            'Description' => 'Bodies are generally pretty good at repairing themselves, but there are limits to what natural Regeneration can achieve (unless you are super-powered or a sea cucumber).',
            'Rules' => '<strong>Regeneration Ordeal</strong> — High Stakes<ul><li>Characters use their Phoenix Facet to handle their regeneration, but they may have a dedicated Annex (like an overly chatty mercenary mutant) or Descendant (or both) to improve on that.</li><li>Natural Regeneration is slow but steady, if the wound can be healed, it will, eventually. </li><li>The Largest Wound that Natural Regeneration can Heal is calculated from the Character’s Phoenix Score doubled (or a regeneration Annex Score could stand in here), as the Limit Pips (so 1 for Distract, 7 for Carnage). So an Average Character with a 13 Phoenix, can heal up to a Crippling Wound themselves.</li><li>Natural Regeneration can attempt to Stabilize any Wound with a Pip Score lower than Half the Phoenix or Annex Boon. Stabilizing a Wound this way is common during combat.</li><li>A Wound is Stabilized by playing the same Suit as the Wound or Hearts <span class="t13ne-redcard">&hearts;</span> to match, or beat, the Pips of the Wound (or Rolling a Score equal to twice the Pips).</li><li><strong>Reopening the Wound</strong> — Until a Wound has completely naturally healed any Flesh Wound can reopen that Wound (the Flesh wound can aggravate any Wound into whatever the regenerating Wound is).</li><li>Regeneration takes time (Pips - Phoenix Facet / Annex Draw as a Yarn Extend Duration) — so an 8 Pip Maiming Wound Healing with a Boon 40(9)[3] Regeneration Power, would heal in a weekend, but a normal Phoenix of 13 [1] would Heal it in about a month). If a Wound has been Treated by another technique (such as first-aid) the wound will naturally heal faster, treating the Pips as -2 for calculating Duration calculation. Wounds already Stabilized by another technique treat Pips as -3.</li></ul>',
            'Applicable_Wounds' => '🤕🤒👤⚡⚒⭐',
            'Best_Result' => 'Stabilizes🤕, then Heals with time.',
            'Worst_Result' => 'Wound Festers☠️.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Name' => 'Physical Therapy',
            'Icon' => '🏈',
            'Description' => 'Natural Regeneration is all well and good, but after you’ve nursed a Wound for a while, you might notice you have lost range of movement, strength, or feeling around the injury. Physical Therapy consists of exercises, motions and activities that can speed up Natural Regeneration 🛏️.',
            'Rules' => '<strong>Exercises</strong> — Stakes - Medium <ul><li>Physical therapy is only useful on Stabilized Naturally Regenerating Wounds.</li><li>Match Suit (or <span class="t13ne-redcard">&hearts;</span>) and Match or Beat Pips of a Wound to half regeneration time, failure will reopen the Wound.</li></ul>',
            'Applicable_Wounds' => '🤕🤒👤⚡⚒',
            'Best_Result' => 'Duration of Natural Regeneration Period is halved.',
            'Worst_Result' => 'Wound Reopens 🎃'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Name' => 'Psychotherapy',
            'Icon' => '🛋️',
            'Description' => 'There are a number of Psychotherapies, ranging from talking therapies to much more modern behaviour modification techniques.',
            'Rules' => '<strong>Psychotherapy Ordeal</strong> — Low Stakes<ul><li>Match Suit (or <span class="t13ne-redcard">♥️</span>) and Match or Beat Pips of a Wound.</li><li>Diff &times;2 if Wounds are Fresh 🍒 or Re-opened 🎃)</li><li>Diff &times;3 for Festering Wounds</li><li>Success Stabilises Psych Wound or halves regeneration time, Failure causes Festering</li></ul>',
            'Applicable_Wounds' => '👤⭐',
            'Best_Result' => 'Wound Stabilized 🤕, or Natural Regeneration 🛏️ Time halved.',
            'Worst_Result' => 'Wound Festers☠️'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Name' => 'Repair',
            'Icon' => '🛠️',
            'Description' => 'Repairing is like healing but for Descendants usually. Repairing can be used by advanced technology on living Flesh such as nanotechnologies, genetic engineering, vita-rays or whatever.',
            'Rules' => '<strong>Repair Ordeal</strong> — Low-Extreme Stakes (varying with the situation)<ul><li>Match Suit (or <span class="t13ne-redcard">♥️</span>) and Match the Difficulty to Remove the Wound in Pips.</li><li>Difficulty is Pips &times; 2 for Festering Wounds</li><li>Success removes the Wound completely. Failure makes the original Wound Fester ☠️ and a Fresh 🍒 copy is applied.</li></ul>',
            'Applicable_Wounds' => '⚡⚒⭐',
            'Best_Result' => 'Removes the Wound completely.',
            'Worst_Result' => 'Wound automatically Festers ☠️ and a Fresh 🍒 copy is applied.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Name' => 'Surgery',
            'Icon' => '💉',
            'Description' => 'You can do a lot with chopping, cutting, sawing and metal pins. New surgical techniques can achieve medical miracles, as long as you don’t mind a scar, or occasional left behind gauze or implement.',
            'Rules' => '<strong>Surgical Ordeal</strong> — Medium-Extreme Stakes (varies by context such as time period, sterility, wound type etc)<ul><li>Surgical Ordeal is a minimum of 3 Stages: Preparation (<span class="t13ne-redcard">&diams;</span> Trump), Cutting (<span class="t13ne-blackcard">&spades;</span> Trump) and Closing (<span class="t13ne-redcard">&hearts;</span> Trump)</li><li>Beat total Pips of all Wounds + (current Boons of the Hitches the Wounds have affected / Boons of Crippled Annexes) over the Stages.</li><li>Each additional Wound to be healed adds a Cutting Stage to the Ordeal, where that Wound will be focused on.</li><li>For each Stage, if you pass the Stage Difficulty, the Wound is replaced with a Stabilized Flesh Wound and the Hitch is renamed as "Surgical Scar" or similar, or the Annex or Proficiency Slot is unlocked.</li><li>Failure in a Cutting Stage means that an additional Fresh (🍒) Flesh Wound is created, and the original Wound remains.</li></ul>',
            'Applicable_Wounds' => '👤⚡⚒',
            'Best_Result' => '<ul><li>Heals Wounds of any type to a Treated 🤒 Flesh Wound.</li><li>Changes “Dying” Hitch to “Surgical Scars”, “Amputated Body part” or similar.</li></ul>',
            'Worst_Result' => '<ul><li>Wounds are re-opened 🎃 (and may Fester ☠️) .</li><li>Additional Fresh 🍒 Flesh Wound created for each wound.</li></ul>'
        ) ,
    );
    public static $plottingTypes = array(
        array(
            'Type' => 'Seat-of-the-Pants',
            'Description' => 'These Referees do not plan their Stories out, they react to the actions of the Characters, using the cards they have to explain how the sides react to the Character’s actions. This sort of play is great under an experienced Referee, but not recommended for beginners.',
            'Rules' => 'Pantsers play cards from their Hand, in any Order, at any time, to create the next section of Plot and then refill their Hand'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Authored',
            'Description' => 'An Author doesn’t have to worry about Players, and can plan out the entire Plot before hand. Some Referees will also do this. Planning each session out in detail, so that they know in advance what will happen. This can go wrong when Players break the Referee’s expectations and don’t defeat the Villain how they thought they would, or run away. Worse yet for games, and the Players, Authored Plots often railroad the Player Characters, making their choices and actions unimportant to the Plot.',
            'Rules' => 'Authors play cards from their Hand during the creation of the Plot to create single Scenes. The Author does not play Yarn Cards during Play usually.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Full-Prep',
            'Description' => ' A Fully Prepped Plot is a technique that can be used to have the Plot prepared, as an Authored Plot might be, but also include branches and choices that they can use when the Player Characters go off the rails. The easiest way to do this is for the Referee to consider at least two different ways of playing any Hand for a Yarn-Telling Scene, before play begins (you can alter the order of the cards played from the Hand to create very different results). This can give flexibility in how the Plot responds to the Characters without having the Referee have to Seat-of-the-Pants anything.',
            'Rules' => 'To Prepare a Plot fully each Scene uses a separate Hand where at least Two variations of Playing the Hand are recorded ahead of time (ideally all variants would be recorded - giving each Scene as many potential ways of playing out as the Plot has sized Hand). Yarn Cards are not played during play, but are narrated by the Yarn-Teller as though they had been.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Hybrid',
            'Description' => 'Hybrid play means that the Referee may Author or Fully Prep the Plot, but if things go too "off-piste" they will use Seat-of-Pants play to get them through it. In many ways this is the best way that the Referee can work. It allows them to map out complex Plots, but doesn’t encourage the Rail-roading of the Players into a particular Story.',
            'Rules' => 'The Plot is created like an Authored or Fully-prepped plot, but during Play the Plot may play cards out of their Hand at any time and then refill their Hand.'
        )
    );
    public static $plotResolutions = array(
        array(
            'Type' => 'Revolution',
            'Description' => 'A revolution does not really resolve the Conflict, but instead reverses the fortunes of the two sides. The Dominant side experiences a Tragic fall, the Depressed side experiences a Dramatic (or Comedic) rise. The original Conflict is technically resolved, but a new reversed Conflict is created. This is a resolution often played for by the Plot . If all else fails, they will put the PC on the top and slink away with their Conflict revolved.',
            'Rules' => 'Pays out according to Plot Rank, the Plot can come back later in the Narrative at the same Rank, but with the Conflict reversed.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Revelation',
            'Description' => 'Not truly a resolution at all, but it ends a phase of Conflict. The “Villain” is exposed, their plans are thwarted, but the actual Conflict is actually still present (and will simply select a new “Villain” and try again). The “Good”/ “Lawful” &nbsp;vs “Evil”/”Criminal” Conflict presented in many Detective novels is an example. The Killer is caught, but society is unaltered by the resolution, the Plot can easily be recycled again with only slight changes. Again a Plot can often try for this style of resolution where nothing is really changed.',
            'Rules' => 'Pays out. This Plot will return with only slight changes (such as different Embodiment) usually at the same Rank.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Rejection',
            'Description' => 'One side (or both) avoids the Conflict. There is no resolution, and the Plot will be promoted one Rank, gain extra Conflict Facets and will spawn at least one new Plot as additional sub-plots about the rejection. Rejections do not pay out to the Characters. If your players refuse to deal with the issue of a local Baron who is enslaving his populace and ride out into the larger world instead, they will return later to discover the Baron is now Emperor having conquered all of his neighbours with his huge slave army. Plots cannot go for this option, it should only be used if the Characters (usually Players) force this resolution.',
            'Rules' => 'Does not Payout to the PCs (they receive no Final Reward). Plot is promoted 1 Rank and will return along with at least one Sub-plot specifically tied to the PCs’ rejection.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Reversion',
            'Description' => 'The situation is unchanged at the end, usually this is because of a failure of the Pressed side of the Conflict to defeat the Dominant. In a detective story, the Reversion will mean the detective failed to solve the crime, perhaps they convicted the wrong person, or they just got away. In the case of a Reversion, the Plot will be promoted a Rank (a Story becomes an Arc) and will return later. Reversions do not payout, but carry over the Yarn into their next Story. All good Plot will seek this resolution and get themselves promoted, unless they are close to the top level of the Plot Hierarchy. Remember though, no Plot will kill all the Pressed side, as at least one Character is needed to start the sequel.',
            'Rules' => 'Failed Resolution, does not pay out. Plot promoted 1 Rank and will return.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Revocation',
            'Description' => 'Despite the best actions of either side, the Loom has failed to work the Conflict and nothing has changed at the end. No one has learnt any lessons. But the Plot is not promoted or demoted. It will simply return again later as essentially the same plot again. This is common to situation-comedies, where everything is back to normal at the end of the story. In a detective novel the murderer wouldn’t be caught and the murder victim would have to be returned to life, somehow, perhaps the whole thing was a mistake.',
            'Rules' => 'No change to the world, Plot remains same Rank, pays out Half normal.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Reconciliation',
            'Description' => 'The Conflict is at least partially resolved by an accord between the two sides. The Dominant side grants conciliations (such as rights, money, makes amends or apologizes) to the Pressed side of the Conflict. A Reconciliation is usually a negotiated settlement, which means that it may not (cannot) completely resolve the Conflict. The Plot is reduced a rank and may return as a Sub-plot at some point. Plots never go for a reconciliation, unless there is no other choice, they do prefer it to an actual Resolution though.',
            'Rules' => 'Pays out according to Rank. Plot -1 Rank, may return as a ’sub-plot’.'
        ) ,
        array(
            'Type' => 'Resolution',
            'Description' => 'True resolution of the Conflict means that the Plot is actually defeated. It will payout its maximum rewards. True resolution usually comes from the Thesis, Antithesis, Synthesis pattern of Dialectic Logic. At it’s simplest, the Resolution is the ideal ending to a romantic plot as it represents marriage of the two Embodiments. A sensible Resolution of Jim the Thief’s Burden-Burden Conflict would probably result in Jim gaining a Burden-Burden “Wealth” skill (or Descendant), it could alternatively pay off Jim’s Vulnerable Hitch, increase his Burden Facet, or even allow him access to the Wielder Core, or Earth Incarna instead. The observant Referee may note what Skills and Descendants a particular character is after, and design a Story specifically to create the required Annex from a Resolved Conflict. While no Plot ever wants to resolve their Conflict, this is the preferred resolution for the Players and the Conflict itself.',
            'Rules' => 'Plot pays out double. Plot is defeated and cannot be used again.'
        ) ,
    );

    public static $conflictSides = array(
        array(
            'Type' => 'Dominant',
            'Description' => 'The Dominant side of the Conflict. The Dominant Embodiment may be the Setting, literally the Environment, or a Monster, or just a more powerful Character than the Pressed Characters, such as an Evil Border Baron. Sometimes the Embodiment, such as the murderer in a Mystery story, does not seem more powerful than the Pressed Characters (in a Mystery, the Detectives), however the killer in this case is embodying Sin, and while the killer may not be Dominant, the police cannot hope to defeat Sin itself.',
            'Rules' => 'The Dominant side is always present in a Conflict, although it may be hidden from view before the final Revelation.' //0

        ) ,
        ['Type' => 'Pressed',
        'Description' => 'The Pressed side of the Conflict may be suppressed, oppressed, depressed or otherwise unempowered. They are often the PCs in Games, but can be the townsfolk, or an oppressed minority in the Barony, or the slightly less militarily based land beyond the Border. The Detectives of a Mystery story, the heroes of a War story.',
        'Rules' => 'The Pressed side is always present in the Conflict, often Embodied within one of the PCs or their Allies.'], //1
        ['Type' => 'Above',
        'Description' => 'The Above side of a Conflict sits in judgement of the Dominant and Pressed side. The Above may be political (the Duke and King, above the Baron), religious (the medieval Church, and particularly the Bishop), divine (the gods themselves, or perhaps their messengers watch and intercede where they are allowed), legal (the Barony may ignore the King’s law only so much), or it can be Moral. In Mystery Stories the Above Side may be politicians, nobles, or the press judging the Detective’s progress.',
        'Rules' => 'Most Conflicts have an Above side, although it may be far removed and so have no direct Embodiment. If the Queen is far away, only eventually will some of the Story come to her attention.'], //2
        ['Type' => 'Internal',
        'Description' => 'Sometimes Conflicts get complicated, with insurgent forces appearing within one or the other of the sides. The Internal Side may exist within all the other sides, or can express a Conflict entirely internally within one Character (creating greater depth). Perhaps the Baron has an Internal Conflict, his conflict with the other Kingdom is simply fall-out from a failed romance. In a Mystery Story the Internal side could be a serial killer inside the police, a policeman undercover within a criminal cabal, or the Detective’s struggle with their own darkness.',
        'Rules' => 'Internal sides are common to all Conflicts that have Pact Descendant Embodiments, but are not required. '], //3
        ['Type' => 'Below',
        'Description' => 'Below the Conflict is the opposite of the Above. These are people who are beneath the normal scope of the Conflict. If the Dominant and Pressed side are two kingdoms at war, the Below could consist of the little people of both kingdoms standing up to their rulers, or perhaps it is a guild or criminal gang taking advantage of the Chaos. In a Mystery the Below side are usually the normal people, the victims of the killer, and the relatives of the victims.',
        'Rules' => 'The Below side should always be represented if both Dominant and Pressed sides are of higher social status. The Below side is difficult to represent if the Pressed side are the lowest rung on the ladder.'], //4
        ['Type' => 'External',
        'Description' => 'Appearing external to the conflict in every way, the External side is of course a part of it all. If the PCs wandered into the Barony then they might be this force. If they are locals, then the External side might be another Border Baron, who plans to out-manoeuvre the Baron, the King and the enemy somehow. If nothing else seems plausible, perhaps Aliens or Increated are involved somehow. In a Mystery Story the External side might be a character from another department, town, country, outer-space, or supernatural, they might be a killer, a cop, the FBI agent who swoops in after a serial killer.',
        'Rules' => 'External side is never required. The Character Embodiments of External side should only be present rarely, and it embodies most often as External embodiments such as Locations, Tone, etc.'], //5
        ['Type' => 'Shadows',
        'Description' => 'The Shadows side of the conflict is always hidden. Sometimes the side may represent those who are not seen, hidden influencers, who will never be revealed. Other times they hint at other Plots moving in the background. Sparingly and rarely the Shadows may reveal some Yarn-Teller, or Increated hiding and influencing events through Twists. In a Mystery story the Shadows side would be the dark underworld, kingpins, robber barons, dark websites, and the ghosts of failed cases.',
        'Rules' => 'The Shadows side will often be present, whether as a direct Character embodiment or simply as a metaphorical shadow from larger Plots.'], //6
        ['Type' => 'DeeperShadows',
        'Description' => 'The DeeperShadows side of the conflict should never exist. It is too hidden to ever be revealed. In a Mystery Story the DeeperShadows would be unknown Illuminati types, engineering these killings for political gains.',
        'Rules' => 'The DeeperShadows side should never truly be present, and usually may only have External or Hidden Embodiments (although they may draw other Embodiments these should never be used as drawn. DeeperShadows also reflect the shadows of greater Plots in any Plot smaller than a Cycle. In a Cycle Plot the DeeperShadows represent those hidden masters, gods, and spirits that guide events, such as Wyrd herself.']
    ); //7
    public static $descendantEdges = array( //this needs Facet Edges removing / including... we'll see.
        ['Type' => 'Affecting',
        'Description' => 'Affecting Descendants have additional effects upon their users and surroundings.',
        'Rule' => 'The Affecting Edge causes the Descendant to cosmetically alter the appearance of the user. The Affecting Glow causes the Surrounding Location or User to be affected as though Side-Stepped by the Master Annex Roll as Yarn when the Descendant is entered, held, drawn or used as appropriate.'],
        ['Type' => 'Annex',
        'Description' => 'The Annex Descendant has additional Annexes beyond normal.',
        'Rule' => 'The Annex Edge grants the Descendant an additional Annex of the highest type available (Proficiency for a Skill, Skill for a Talent, etc). The Annex Glow grants an additional Annex of type "equal" to the Master Annex or Super-Annex, and one of each lower Annex type down to Proficiency.'],
        ['Type' => 'Assault',
        'Description' => 'An Assault Descendant is intended to cause greater damage to its targets, but is draining on the Descendant.',
        'Rule' => 'An Assault Edge can make one Attack per Scene at Extreme Stakes and may Roll the Descendant’s Master Annex Die and add the result to the Pips for the Attack for a cost of 1 Stored Chi. An Assault Glow makes one Attack per Ordeal Round at Extreme Stakes automatically, and adds the Descendant’ Edge Tier Limit to the Pips of that Attack for 1 Chi. '],
        ['Type' => 'Back-up',
        'Description' => 'An Back-up Descendant is capable of calling or sending back-up, assistance, or aid. It is common on Pact Descendants.',
        'Rule' => 'A Back-up Edge can summon one member of the Pact from a lower Tier or one Extra with a Boon smaller than the Master Annex Boon of the Descendant. A Back-Up Glow can summon all same or lower Tiered members of the Pact or Summon a number of Characters equal to the Total Stored Chi in the Descendant (see sway table). Summoning will take time based on the Master Annex Boon as a Chi Limit Duration, but may be accelerated by paying Chi from the Descendant.'],
        ['Type' => 'Better',
        'Description' => 'A Better Descendant is just better than others.',
        'Rule' => 'A Better Edge adds the current number of Edges to every rolled Score (does not effect the Tier Limits). A Better Glow adds +2 for each Edge and +5 Score for each Glow.'],
        ['Type' => 'Changes',
        'Description' => 'The Changes Descendant grants a Descendant a personality of sorts. This is often a animistic spirit the User associates with the Descendant, but it may be communicative such as an AI assistant. It is certainly true that the Descendant gains Sway in new ways and may even have its own abilities that it can employ.',
        'Rule' => 'The Changes Edge grants the Descendant an I-Ching Hexagram (with a Gain that usually pays 1). The Changes Glow grants a second Hexagram to the Descendant that is normally the same as the previous one, granting that Hexagram’s "Unchanging" ability (or Changing Lines) to the Descendant.'],
        ['Type' => 'Dark',
        'Description' => 'Dark Descendants are wreathed in shadows and darkness.',
        'Rule' => 'A Descendant with a Dark Edge has a shroud of darkness that engulfs it.  This clouds an area equal to the Edge Tier Limit as a Size, with an unfavourable lighting condition or shadow for non-Users (-2). A Dark Glow is a deeper darkness that renders everyone in the radius apart from the User effectively blind (-13), or affects them with an Umbral effect.'],
        ['Type' => 'Doomed',
        'Description' => 'Doomed Descendants have a greater purpose, and can be leveraged by Characters to achieve theirs.',
        'Rule' => 'Doomed Edges allow a Wyrd Tarot card to be played upon the Descendant, that will linger permanently. Court cards are permanently active in their desired facing for the Descendant and any User, but Non-Court cards must be activated for 1 Chi. Doomed Glows allow the Descendant to use the lingering Doom card as a Yarn Card at anytime by the User (even Grunts can Yarn-Tell a little with this Descendant).'],
        ['Type' => 'Diabolic/Unseelie',
        'Description' => 'Diabolic or Unseelie Descendants are usually associated with devils, demons, and Unseelie faeries.',
        'Rule' => 'Diabolic / Unseelie Edges grant a Descendant a bonus to all Yang Facet Actions equal to the number of Edges &times; 2, but exude an aura may be sensed as a malevolent force. Diabolic / Unseelie Glows raise this bonus to +3 for each Edge and +10 for each Glow, but the aura is now visibly present as a flame, shadow, or sparks. It also creates a noise when used, like screaming souls, moans, whispering voices, or raging fires, and has an associated smell such as brimstone, corruption, or excrement.'],
        ['Type' => 'Discount',
        'Description' => 'Discount Descendants grant the user discounts on other Descendants that they purchase. This can represent staff or guild discounts, loyalty cards, insider knowledge, old school networks, or just being rich.',
        'Rule' => 'Discount Edges grant a discount on purchases of other Descendants, usually based on genre conventions and social conventions (subject to Yarn-Teller and Referee agreement) equal to the Edge Tier Limit / Master Annex Score in Chi for each Edge. Discount Glows increase this ability to the Master Annex Boon for each Glow. Purchases retain a minimum cost of 1 Chi.'],
        ['Type' => 'Divine/Seelie',
        'Description' => 'Divine or Seelie Descendants are usually associated with saints, gods, and Seelie faeries.',
        'Rule' => 'Divine / Seelie Edges grant a Descendant a bonus to all Yin Facet Actions equal to the number of Edges &times; 2, but exude an aura that may be sensed as a benevolent force. Divine / Seelie Glows raise this bonus to +3 for each Edge and +10 for each Glow, but the aura is now visibly present as a flame, frost, or light. It also creates a noise when used, like a bell ring, singing choirs, whispered prayers, or susurrating leaves, and has an associated perfume, such as flowers, fresh pine, incense or fresh baking.'],
        ['Type' => 'Effective',
        'Description' => 'Effective Descendants are more effective than others. ',
        'Rule' => 'A Descendant with an Effective Edge adds a Success Level once per Scene. As an Effective Glow this increases to adding a Success Level to every Action.'],
        ['Type' => 'Eternal',
        'Description' => 'Eternal Descendants never age, or are damaged, until they are destroyed.',
        'Rule' => 'The Eternal Edge causes a Descendant to not age. It will always maintain the appearance of whatever age it had when the Edge was added. The Eternal Glow increases this to make the State of the Descendant also unchanging. Additionally, no Wound will affect the Eternal Descendant until it is affected by any Mortal or Carnage Wound when it will immediately collapse into dust.'],
        ['Type' => 'Extended',
        'Description' => 'Extended Descendants are customised to make them permanently bigger somehow. Often this pertains to a single dimension, such as length (a Stretch Limousine), height, or duration (time such as, Chronoliths that last longer than an Instant).',
        'Rule' => 'The Extended Edge increases the selected dimension slightly. Increasing in size can increase Reach or add a new Size Annex to the Descendant equal to the number of Edges (e.g. 3 Edges could grant Reach or Size +3), but is most important for extending the duration of normally instantaneous effects. The Extended Glow increases the Scale of the Owner by +1 (even beyond their number of Hitches), and increases the Reach or Size Annex by 2 per Edge and 3 per Glow'],
        ['Type' => 'Fast',
        'Description' => 'Fast Descendants are quicker than others. ',
        'Rule' => 'A Descendant with an Fast Edge reduces the RT of all Annexes by the total number of Edges and all GRTs by 1. The Fast Glow reduces GRT by the number of Glows +1 and RT is at most 1.'],
        ['Type' => 'Fortunate',
        'Description' => 'Fortunate Descendants are less likely to be randomly difficult to handle, or explosive, unstable, etc.',
        'Rule' => 'If a Descendant with an Fortunate Edge rolls less than average then it automatically takes the average instead, this also grants a re-roll of one Proficiency die during a Proficiency Crisis. When raised to an Fortunate Glow, the Descendant always rolls maximum.'],
        ['Type' => 'Hardened',
        'Description' => 'A Hardened Descendant is tougher than you might expect. In some cases it may be nigh on indestructible.',
        'Rule' => 'A Hardened Edge can store one additional Wound on one of the Descendant’s Annexes. A Hardened Glow will store an extra Wound on each Annex, and may ignore 1 Wound completely.'],
        ['Type' => 'Knowledge',
        'Description' => 'Knowledge Descendants grant their User access to their own Proficiencies as though they were the Users.',
        'Rule' => 'Knowledge Edges allow the Wielder to access one Proficiency from each Annex of the Descendant as though it was their own. Knowledge Glows grant the User access to all the Proficiencies in the Descendant as though they were their own.'],
        ['Type' => 'Light',
        'Description' => 'Light Descendants are lit with an aura that only the User can see.',
        'Rule' => 'A Descendant with an Light Edge has a flickering aura that activates when the Descendant is used. This Aura lights an area equal to the Edge Tier Limit as a Size, usually only the User can see by this light, but it may be visible to everyone in a high magical field or setting. A Light Glow grants each and every action with the Edged Descendant a specific Facet Success, chosen by the Creator.'],
        ['Type' => 'Monstrous',
        'Description' => 'Those who wield the Descendant, or enter the Location or Space become Monsters.',
        'Rule' => 'Each Monstrous Edge grants the User (or those in the Location) access to a Monster Facet (usually the Descendant Incarna or Master Annex Channelling Facet). However, the Monster Pool is restricted by the Descendant, to the Edge Tier Cost Reduced cards. A Monstrous Glow grants full unrestricted access to the Monster Pool and grants access to Monster Facets of both the Master Annex Root and Channel Facets.'],
        ['Type' => 'Paid',
        'Description' => 'A Descendant or with a Paid Edge is cheaper to use than others of its type.',
        'Rule' => 'A Descendant with a Paid Edge allows its user to ignore one Umbral or Hitch when using the Descendant. A Descendant with a Paid Glow will negate all Descendant Hitches and Umbrals when using the Descendant.'],
        ['Type' => 'Personal',
        'Description' => 'Personal Descendants are intended to be used only by their Creator or Owner',
        'Rule' => 'Descendants with a Personal Edge add +2 Score per Edge when used by the person who set the Edge, but have a -2 per Edge if wielded by someone else. The Personal Glow will attempt to attack anyone who does not have a Personal Edge that attempts to use the Descendant and adds 1 Failure Level to every action they attempt with the Descendant.'],
        ['Type' => 'Personality',
        'Description' => 'The Personality Descendant becomes, or at least seems close to, sentient. It definitely displays at least an animal-like personality. Combined with Changes this can create a truly intelligent and real personality.',
        'Rule' => 'The Personality Edge can grant a Descendant either a Master Annex Channelling Facet Persona, or a Master Annex Root Facet Core. These Cores may affect the user if Referee and Yarn-Teller deem it appropriate. As a Glow this will grant both, and effectively replace the Descendant with an appropriate Archetype / Extra Character.'],
        ['Type' => 'Rank',
        'Description' => 'Rank Descendants allow grades of Membership for Pacts (or similar).',
        'Rule' => 'Each Rank Edge purchased buys a Rank within the Pact/Descendant, the number of possible Rank Edges gives the number of subordinates within the organization that the Rank has (as Yarn Group Size on the Sway Table) E.g. a Military Organization Pact, may have Rank 1 (Corporal) 3-10 Subordinates, Rank 2 (Sergeant) Dozen to 39 subordinates, Rank 3 (Lieutenant) 40-84 subordinates, Rank 4 (Captain) 85-374 subordinates, and so on. A Rank Glow will add Two Rank Edges, and grant access to another Edge such as Mentor or Proficient. Subordinates are expected to follow the orders of those with a higher Rank, or face expulsion from the Pact. Rank also counts as a Pay-day Edge but all Chi rewards are halved.'],
        ['Type' => 'Relieving',
        'Description' => 'Relieving Descendants provide Stress Relief for their User.',
        'Rule' => 'A Relieving Edge Relieves Stress for the User. Typically the Edge will Relieve Stress equal to the Rolled Score each use. A Relieving Glow will Relieve all Stress when drawn or weilded.'],
        ['Type' => 'Shielding',
        'Description' => 'Shielding Descendants help protect themselves and their User.',
        'Rule' => 'A Shielding Edge creates a Descendant or Defensive Style Pool Prepared Defence, each time it is wielded. This Prepared Defence always has a minimum card of a 2 and a maximum card Pip equal to the Master Annex Maximum Score. E.g. A d6 Sword would create a 2-6 Prepared Defence. A Shielding Edge adds a total number of Pips equal to the Edge Tier Cost &times; the total number of Edges, e.g. the d6 sword with a Shielding Edge and two others would create a Prepared Defence for 2-6 Pips and 18 Pips total each time it is drawn. A Shielding Glow creates a Prepared Defence that is always up and can block all Ordeal cards. It uses the current stored Chi as the Pips of the Defence, but will lose 1 Chi for each card stopped.'],
        ['Type' => 'Shrinking',
        'Description' => 'Shrinking Descendants are customised to make them capable of collapsing or shrinking somehow. Usually this Shrinking will effect the Reach (a magical shrinking staff, collapsable baton), Size (collapsible ladders or tents) or Duration (Limiting normally permanent effects such as making a temporary hole).',
        'Rule' => 'The Shrinking Edge decreases the Size, Reach or Extend Duration (or more often, increases the Limit Duration) of a Descendant by the number of Edges when required. e.g. 3 Edges, 1 of which was Shrinking, would grant Reach or Size of -3 or a Duration Limit of a Decade. The Shrinking Glow allows the User to change size with the Descendant, and decreases the Reach, Size or Duration by 2 per Edge and 3 per Glow as Chi. This can allow a Shrinking Glow along with two other Edges to alter Reach or Size by -7 (which can shrink the User to the size of a Bee), or let you kill someone for 4 months before they get better.'],
        ['Type' => 'Stressful',
        'Description' => 'Stressful Descendants generate Stress for their User and the Target.',
        'Rule' => 'A Stressful Edge creates Stress for the User and the Target each use. The User Gains the generated Score from the Die roll as Stress. The Target Gains Stress always equal to the Maximum possible roll. A Stressful Glow mulitples the Stress gained by the total number of Edges, which can quickly become Strains or Shocks and Traumas. Use with care.'],
        ['Type' => 'Wielded',
        'Description' => 'A Wielded Descendant grants its owner or user an Edge of their own.',
        'Rule' => 'A Wielded Edge grants the User or Owner one of the other Edges that effects themselves. A Wielded Glow grants either another Glow to the User or all Edges, as the Owner decides.'],
    );

    public static $NPCProficiencies = array(
        ['Circumstance' => 'NPC shouldn’t be doing this',
        'Modifier' => 'Halve Score'],
        ['Circumstance' => 'NPC might be doing this',
        'Modifier' => '+3'],
        ['Circumstance' => 'NPC can do this',
        'Modifier' => '+7'],
        ['Circumstance' => 'NPC is good at this',
        'Modifier' => '+10'],
        ['Circumstance' => 'NPC is great at this',
        'Modifier' => '+13'],
        ['Circumstance' => 'NPC is an expert at this',
        'Modifier' => '+16'],
        ['Circumstance' => 'NPC is a world leader at this',
        'Modifier' => '+21'],
    );
    public static $experienceTiers = array(
        array(
            'Type' => 'Fresh',
            'Description' => 'A new Character that has little or no experience of the real world, they may have some education, street smarts, battle experience, or professional training, but never all four.',
            'Rules' => 'Fresh Characters generally begin with the minimum number of Hitches for their Type, but may add up to 2 additional Hitches. Fresh Characters often start with a negative Scale and usually begin play as Young-Adults or Kids.',
            'Min_Hitches' => 'Normal for Type',
            'Max_Hitches' => 'Up to +2 over Minimum'
        ) , //0
        array(
            'Type' => 'Experienced',
            'Description' => 'Any Character that has survived a few Stories, or Chapters, is usually considered an Experienced Character. Some Narratives may require a Character to remain Fresh for longer than this, but if they have received new Hitches, then they are probably experienced.',
            'Rules' => 'Experienced Characters generally have at least one more Hitch than their minimum, and usually have at least 3 more than the minimum. They are generally around Half full of Hitches and at least one is usually Resolved.',
            'Min_Hitches' => 'Minimum for Type +1',
            'Max_Hitches' => 'Up to Half of Max for the Type'
        ) , //1
        array(
            'Type' => 'Veteran',
            'Description' => 'Veteran Characters have survived through at least one Volume Plot, and have Resolved at least two of their early Hitches.',
            'Rules' => 'Veteran Characters generally are within 3 of their Maximum Number of Hitches for their type and always have at least Half their Hitches either filled or Resolved.',
            'Min_Hitches' => 'Half of Max for Type',
            'Max_Hitches' => 'Max for Type -1'
        ) , //2
        array(
            'Type' => 'Maxed',
            'Description' => 'A Maxed Character has generally experienced enough of the world that nothing surprises them anymore. Maxed Characters have typically survived several Volumes and completed at least one Character Arc.',
            'Rules' => 'Maxed Characters simply have their Maximum number of Hitches possible for that type (and a Scale to match). Usually a Maxed Character will have at least Half of their Hitches Resolved.',
            'Min_Hitches' => 'Max-Hitches for Type. Half of them Resolved',
            'Max_Hitches' => 'Max-Hitches for Type'
        ) , //3

    );
    public static $ageCategories = array(
        array(
            'Type' => 'New-born',
            'Description' => 'New-born Characters are usually pretty defenceless things. Although xenomorphic space wasps and the like can be a lot less defenceless than say a human new born.',
            'Rules' => 'Sentient New-born creatures are largely defenceless and usually unplayable. They can often not communicate and can rarely process sensory data accurately.',
            'Scale_Modifier' => '-4',
            'Proficiency_Dice' => '1d3-1'
        ) , //0
        array(
            'Type' => 'Infant',
            'Description' => 'Small Children, often quite mobile and if sentient usually talking, although they have limited vocabularies.',
            'Rules' => 'In general Infants are not just small people, they are still largely defenceless, although many can communicate effectively with their limited vocabulary. Infants are intelligent and manipulative, still trying to work out all the rules of their social structure, and are likely to test boundaries.',
            'Scale_Modifier' => '-3',
            'Proficiency_Dice' => '1d3'
        ) , //1
        array(
            'Type' => 'Kid',
            'Description' => 'Kids are still Children, but are more like mini-adults, they are weaker than adults and have less general knowledge and education, but make up for that by being adaptable and learning fast.',
            'Rules' => 'Essentially kids are small adults, they can fight, etc, but aren\'t very powerful. They do however learn faster, and are usually placed in full-time education during this period to take advantage of that. Kids may have multiple Hobbies in diverse fields, some of which may be connected with aspirations or parental pressures.',
            'Scale_Modifier' => '-2',
            'Proficiency_Dice' => '1d4'
        ) , //2
        array(
            'Type' => 'Young-Adult',
            'Description' => 'Young Adults, or Teens are almost adult.',
            'Rules' => 'Almost fully grown, although their mental facilities are sometimes hormonally impaired, in humans Young-Adults are less good at planning and are more emotional than adults. Generally have not completed their education, but in specific areas may be very knowledgable. Often have more than one Hobby activity.',
            'Scale_Modifier' => '-1',
            'Proficiency_Dice' => '1d5'
        ) , //3
        array(
            'Type' => 'Adult',
            'Description' => 'Fully grown and considered an adult by their society.',
            'Rules' => 'Normal, fully grown and educated. Expected to have at least one area of professional specialisation and often a Hobby too.',
            'Scale_Modifier' => '0',
            'Proficiency_Dice' => '1d6'
        ) , //4
        array(
            'Type' => 'Aged',
            'Description' => 'Aged Characters are always Experienced or Veteran Characters. As Aged Characters age they generally accumulate Hitches, such as "Fatigued", "Scars", "Madness", "Vague" that limit their abilities.',
            'Rules' => 'Experienced or Veteran only. Hitches may mimic the affects of old age, such as Physical Weakness, Dementia, etc. They suffer from Crisis less often than even Adults, but as a result learn slower. Expected to have numerous areas of professional and hobbyist level experience.',
            'Scale_Modifier' => '0',
            'Proficiency_Dice' => '1d8'
        ) , //5

    );
    public static $charTypes = array(
        array(
            'Type' => 'Extra',
            'Description' => 'A simple NPC, not even really a Character at all, although they are still be characters in a narrative sense. Vex and Chorus characters are particularly inconsequential and one-dimensional. They are the background characters of a crowd scene, individually they are unimportant to the Plot or Conflict, but they will be important to someone',
            'Rules' => 'Extras are just sentient Descendants created by the Plot or a Yarn-Teller, not really Characters in the true sense. Extras can have a Scale of -3 to +20 as it isn’t attached to the number of Hitches, but instead based on the Plot that created them. Extras may have Geometries, Personas and Cores. They may have access to I-Ching, but usually do not. Normally Extras have a single Annex that they use for all rolls (it is their Skills, Talents and Powers). Treat normal rolls as appropriate for the Extra. Skills draw one less card than a Talent. Talents draw an extra card than a Skill. Powers draw Twice the number of cards of a Skill. Super-Annexes draw twice the cards of a Talent. Play as normal (Skill plays 1, Talent plays 2, Power plays 3) with normal GRT costs. You can detail the Skills, Talents and Powers separately for each one, but really why bother. Instead add a Pip bonus to each card to balance the combat (Talent: add Half Scale, Power: add Scale, Super-Skill: add Scale x3 as a rough example rule – or add Nimbeds instead).<br/> Vexes have no Hexagram, no Personality Annex and may only gain Chi from Geometry or by triggering Hitches.<br/>',
            'Element' => array(
                'Extra',
                'Pattern'
            )
        ) , //0
        array(
            'Type' => 'Lite',
            'Description' => 'Lite Characters are a very simplified Character that may be used as NPCs or PCs in a either a simplified game or as an Alternate.',
            'Rules' => 'Lite Characters essentially multiply Proficiencies rather than building actual Annexes. They are quick to build and easy to play. Lite Characters can also use Extras as Alts.',
            'Element' => array(
                'Lite',
                'Extra'
            )
        ) , //1
        array(
            'Type' => 'Archetype',
            'Description' => 'Archetypes are simplified Full Characters that the Ref uses for really important NPCs, they are real Characters, but are less detailed than standard Characters.',
            'Rules' => 'Archetypes simplify Full Characters with card Archetypes, and limit the number of Facets of different boons by combining them into Stats (often 1-6 Stats of Boons between 8-18) for ease of creation and use. It is not unusual to begin play, especially for NPCs using Archetype Characters. They are usually migrated to Full Characters if they are reused.',
            'Element' => array(
                'Archetype',
                'Character'
            )
        ) , //2
        array(
            'Type' => 'Detailed',
            'Description' => 'Detailed Characters are intended for PCs, they are the best Character type for all your lead Characters (unless you require Full Characters).',
            'Rules' => 'Detailed Characters are created around a complete set of Facets (although they may share Boons into Stats, of course), a Personality Annex, with (potentially a Super-Annex) Powers, Talents, Skills, Proficiencies etc. Detailed Characters usually have a very limited number of Alts.',
            'Element' => array(
                'Detailed',
                'Weaver',
                'Character'
            )
        ) , //3
        array(
            'Type' => 'Full',
            'Description' => 'Full Characters are the pinnacle of T13 Characters, and are required for the most powerful and important NPCs and PCs. Most Yarn-Tellers, Fae and Bulm&auml;s Characters require Full Characters if they are going to be encountered more than once.',
            'Rules' => 'Full Characters are essentially a pool of abilities from all their Alts. They are essentially a group of Detailed Characters living in a single trans-dimensional body.',
            'Element' => array(
                'Full',
                'Weaver',
                'Character'
            )
        ) //4

    );
    public static $extraTypes = array(
        array(
            'Type' => 'Vex',
            'Master_Annex' => 'Skill equal to any PC Skill',
            'Description' => 'Vexes are simplistic and weak animals and characters, they are static, unchanging stereotypes and one-dimensional characters, they are intended for small animals and unimportant none-speaking roles. They generally have little effect on the outcome of a story.',
            'Rules' => 'Vexes are made from a single Skill Annex, usually named for the Extra or "Living" or "Doing Stuff" that the Vex uses for all actions. Vexes have no Hexagram, no Personality Annex and may only gain Chi from Geometry or by triggering Hitches. Vexes cannot spend Chi except on their own actions. Vexes are not really limited in Hitches at all, you can add them for flavour. Vexes can have a Scale of -3 to +20 as it is not restricted by Hitches, but by the Plot.',
            'Min-Hitches' => 0,
            'Max-Hitches' => 24,
            'Woe_Gain' => '1 Twist when triggered',
            'Hitch_Gain' => '1 Yarn when triggered',
            'Gain' => 'Normally 1 Yarn for Persona / Core / I-Ching / Geometry gains',
            'Max_Stored_Chi' => 'Master Annex Highest possible rolled Score'
        ) , //0
        array(
            'Type' => 'Chorus',
            'Master_Annex' => 'Talent equal to any PC Talent',
            'Description' => 'Chorus are simple NPCs (Secondary or Tertiary Characters) that may have a larger part in a Story. They are usually at best two-dimensional characters, and are seldom named roles beyond "Townsperson #3" or "Second Guard".',
            'Rules' => 'Chorus are usually made from a single Talent Annex, although they may also have Skills as a Talent Descendant. Chorus have no Hexagram, no Personality Annex and may only gain Chi from Geometry or by triggering Hitches. Chorus cannot spend Chi except on their own actions. Chorus are not really limited in Hitches at all, you can add them for flavour. Chorus can have a Scale of -3 to +20 as it is not restricted by Hitches, but by the Plot.',
            'Min-Hitches' => 0,
