            'Sway_Gain' => 'Personality Annex Draw Yin/Yang'
        ) , //9
        array(
            'Type' => 'Yarn-Teller',
            'Description' => 'Yarn-Teller is the term we use for Characters that can manipulate reality to create Narratives of their own devising. Faery-Nobles, Demi-Gods, Arch-Mages, Superheroes, Grand-Mercari, Solos, Brass etc...',
            'Rules' => 'Yarn-Tellers are able to Doom-Weave with Yarn cards. Side-step between realities, create metaphor bubble realities and manipulate Space-Time directly.',
            'Min-Hitches' => 6,
            'Max-Hitches' => 13,
            'Woe_Gain' => 'Marks in Twists/Yarn when triggered',
            'Hitch_Gain' => 'Banes in Chi when triggered',
            'Gain' => 'Personality Boon Chi for Persona/Core/I-Ching gains',
            'Max_Stored_Chi' => 'Personality Super-Value',
            'Sway_Gain' => 'Personality Annex Score Yin/Yang'
        ) , //10
        array(
            'Type' => 'Demon-Lord',
            'Description' => 'When a Demon gains enough power (or adds additional Souls enough to "evolve") or a Yarn-Teller has a Woe Hitch, they may become a Yarn-Telling Greater Demon, a Demon-lord. Demon-lords are the most versatile Characters in the system, you can use them to model everything from Tyrants to Deranged Super-Villains. Hobgoblins that gain enough power to be considered Demon-lords usually go by the Title of Orc, Ogre or Ettin instead. They are generally considered more brutish, and less sophisticated than Demon-lords.',
            'Rules' => 'Demon-lords can Yarn-Tell and use Twists too. The most powerful Demon-lords are almost Plots in their own right, creating Stories and Arcs by their whim.',
            'Min-Hitches' => 7,
            'Max-Hitches' => 14,
            'Woe_Gain' => 'Marks in Twists when triggered',
            'Hitch_Gain' => 'Banes in Chi when triggered',
            'Gain' => 'Personality Annex Boon Chi for Persona/Core/I-Ching gains',
            'Max_Stored_Chi' => 'Personality Annex Super-Value',
            'Sway_Gain' => 'Personality Annex Score Yin/Yang'
        ) , //11
        array(
            'Type' => 'Bulmäs',
            'Description' => 'The Bulmäs are either shape-shifting embodied spirits of nature, or Nullite-enhanced, organic, Terra-forming engines, and are Soul-eaters, soul-farmers, or soul-protectors, depending upon who you ask, and which path you are talking about. They are responsible for many stories of lizard-people, werewolves, centaurs, the Minotaur and other beast-men. Bulmäs may add other souls to their own by eating, or for the most powerful just meeting, people.',
            'Rules' => 'Bulmäs use their Wyrd Tarot hand to shape-shift and walk the Lea to travel between Locations. They can refer to it as a Lea Hand as it represents the local Lea paths, rather than the Local Tapestry. A Bulmäs is usually limited by the number of souls they carry. Bulmäs can only Lea Walk once they have two Souls, and are limited to the paths that reflect their lifestyle (Herd (Grunts and Heroes) / Hunter (Mostly Heroes) / Broccen (Territorial Heroes and Yarn-Tellers) / Vermis (the Solo Lord Vermis is all Vermis, although some Alternates are less well integrated than others) / Labyrinthine (Yarn-Tellers that guard the Labyrinth and save lost souls) / All-walker (Yarn-Tellers who act as Lea Guardians and can duplicate souls) / Hell-Walker [also Hell-goats, Hell-bats, Hell-cats, Hell-hounds, Hell-boars, Hell-wyrms and Ettins] (Bulmäs with a Woe Hitch, highly prized by the Increated, they hunt souls for their masters, or duplicate them for them)). Lea cards are played and remain in place on a character like Wyrd Tarot Court cards, where they add their Pips to all Scores the Bulmäs generates that reflects this animal form. Lea cards do allow some Bulmäs to manipulate the Tapestry (as Wyrd Tarot or Yarn Cards).',
            'Min-Hitches' => 1,
            'Max-Hitches' => 13,
            'Woe_Gain' => 'Varies from 1 Twist for Hell-goats, to Ruins Twists for Hell-hounds, to Marks Twists for Hell-wyrms, Ettins and Hell-Walkers. Some Bulm&aumlaut;s such as Vermis can gain Marks Yarn instead of Twists.',
            'Hitch_Gain' => 'Varies as Grunt, Hero or Yarn-Teller by number of Souls carried and path.',
            'Gain' => 'Personality Annex Boon Chi for Persona/Core/I-Ching gains',
            'Max_Stored_Chi' => 'Personality Annex Super-Value',
            'Sway_Gain' => 'Personality Annex Score Yin/Yang'
        ) , //12
        array(
            'Type' => 'Kaiju',
            'Description' => 'Kaiju are how we describe enormous Characters, be they whales, self-aware vehicles, ogres, dinosaurs, dragons, giant-robots, radioactive-dinosaurs, mech-suits, clanks, battle-toons, demon-princes, living-gods, or eldritch cosmic-horrors.',
            'Rules' => 'Any Character with a Size Annex is technically a Kaiju. They may be able to Yarn-Tell, Twist or Doom-Weave, depending on what sort of Character has been given a Size Annex. Size Annexes do not have Proficiencies to create Value, but are based instead on the size required. Kaiju may use their Size Annex to any reasonable effect (pound attacks, resisting most weapons, soaking damage, stepping huge distances, etc).',
            'Min-Hitches' => 1,
            'Max-Hitches' => 24,
            'Woe_Gain' => 'Marks in Twists/Yarn when triggered',
            'Hitch_Gain' => 'Banes in Chi when triggered',
            'Gain' => 'Size Annex Boon Chi for Persona/Core/I-Ching gains',
            'Max_Stored_Chi' => 'Personality Super-Value',
            'Sway_Gain' => 'Size Annex Score Yin/Yang'
        ) , //13
        array(
            'Type' => 'Neechies',
            'Description' => 'Neechies are the sensation of motion out of the corner of the eye. They are the least of the Increated, stirring the edges of human vision in the hopes that the Character will believe them to be something, making the Neechie a true Increated. In T13, if you think you just saw something out of the corner of your eye, then be very careful what you think it might be, you may have just summoned an Increated and gifted it a Nightmare Form.',
            'Rules' => 'Neechies are non-existent Characters, that have no Character sheet, but can suddenly "exist" if they are believed in by another Character. Neechies are nameless, and seek to be given any identity. To this end they can store Success and Failure Levels and transfer them to those who believe.',
            'Min-Hitches' => 0,
            'Max-Hitches' => 0,
            'Woe_Gain' => 'Cannot have Hitches',
            'Hitch_Gain' => 'Cannot have Hitches',
            'Gain' => '1 Chi for Persona/Core/I-Ching gains where possible. +5 Chi, +1 Twist and +1 Transferable Success or Failure Level when believed-in or imagined into existence.',
            'Max_Stored_Chi' => '13 Chi',
            'Sway_Gain' => '1 Yin/Yang'
        ) , //14
        array(
            'Type' => 'Increated',
            'Description' => 'Increated are the beings that were left out of the Creation of T13 by the Prime Anomaly, instead these beings were conjured into existence by human imagination and interactions between semi-deleted code chunks in the Nullite systems the Anomaly was made from. They are Neechies with Hitches, who banded together for co-operation initially, but later factionated. Increated usually dwell in both a "real-world" like T13 and the realm of Shades, which was created and populated by Garner accidentally during the Paradox War. Shades is a sub-real space that only exists because of the force of will of Garner, the horrific Dominion of Blakk, and the power of the souls being forced to believe it into existence so they can survive there. These souls are recruited, stolen, and traded by the most powerful Increated (those with the shortest Names) from various universes by various means, Mot for example created the Kirk of Death in the T13 Universe to allow him to collect the souls of the dead. If an Increated is named incorrectly by a powerful Character it may cause the Increated’s name to change (becoming shorter and adding Hitches usually).',
            'Rules' => 'Increated are only capable of having a Facet Value in a Facet they have a Hitch in, and will always have a Facet Boon one lower than their Hitch. Otherwise they can be treated as any of the Goblin — Demon-lord types, depending on the number of Hitches. Increated can also have a Size Annex, in which case see Kaiju. Increated Names are 25 syllables long, less one for each Hitch (or Resolved Hitch) they have, to a minimum of 1 Syllable. Increated can convert Tao Sway directly into Twists on a 1 for 1 basis, and so usually steal the Yarn created by Woes and replace it with a similar number of Twists for any Character with a Woe.',
            'Min-Hitches' => 1,
            'Max-Hitches' => 24,
            'Woe_Gain' => 'Banes Twists',
            'Hitch_Gain' => 'Banes Twists',
            'Gain' => 'Personality Annex Score Twists for Persona/Core/I-Ching gains.  ',
            'Max_Stored_Chi' => 'Personality Annex Super-Value',
            'Sway_Gain' => '1 Yin/Yang'
        ) //15

    );
    public static $heroAbilities = array( 
        //
        array(
            'Ability' => 'Hand',
            'Description' => 'Some Heroes seem unnaturally powerful, as though they have hidden reserves that they can tap when needed. Sometimes these hidden reserves can power supernatural abilities.',
            'Rules' => 'Heroes can Draw cards to their Hand. Typically the Hand holds 5 Cards (although some Character Types and Cores may add more). Hero&apos;s may Play cards from their Hand during Ordeals (adding to Actions or as Actions), or may be played as Wyrd Tarot or Lea Cards. Characters without a Hand are limited in what they can accomplish with Shapeshifting and Doom-Weaving.'
        ),
        array(
        'Ability' => 'Chi Boosting',
        'Description'=>'Heroes can almost always spend Chi to boost their own Scores, many can also boost the Scores of their allies.',
        'Rules' => 'Typically Chi adds +2 Score or +1 Pip per point of Chi spent. However this can vary with setting and Character.<br/>Larger amounts of Chi may create more Score such as 2 Chi adding +5, 3 +8, etc.'),
         array(
        'Ability' => 'Increase Character Scale',
        'Description'=>'People grow and change with time. Experience and practise hones a heroes body, mind, and spirit.',
        'Rules' => 'Increasing in Character Scale is equal to the total Yin and Yang that the Character can Store or a Hero&apos;s Maximum stored Chi (which is often Cheaper). Scale adds directly to all Facet Boons and increases the available Values for Annexes.'),
        array(
        'Ability' => 'Doom-Weaving',
        'Description'=>'Heroes that have some F&aelig; Blood can often manipulate the Tapestry, altering events around them in minor and major ways.',
        'Rules' => 'Typically Doom-Weavers may Play Cards from their Hands as Wyrd Tarot effects.<br/>Doom-weavers can also typically convert Ordeal Cards into Wyrd Tarot cards for a Chi Cost or Difficulty.'),
        array(
        'Ability' => 'Soul-Walking /  Dream-Trodding',
        'Description'=>'Heroes that have more than one Soul and at least one Bulmäs Soul, or are descended from certain F&aelig; Bloodlines can physically travel via another realm, typically described as the Lea or the Tapestry. Bulmäs Lea paths follow the trails and migratory routes of specific animals, if you&apos;ve seen the same type of butterfly in two places then a butterfly path will connect those places.<br/>Trods are similar, but connect places that have similar names, purposes, or real roads that connect them; Trods allow F&aelig; to skip from any crossroad, doorway, threshold, or similar liminal space, to any other. Trods and Lea Paths can both access Dreams, Memories or minds if the right paths are available.',
        'Rules' => 'Soul-Walkers typically use their Hand of cards to represent the Lea Paths that are available to them locally. The Bulmäs perceive the Lea as composed of coloured animal spirit paths. Walking the path is an expression of how familiar the Bulmäs is with that animal and they can present Soul-Stakes Ordeals that must be overcome.<br/>Only certain paths are open to certain Bulmäs, only All-Walkers can walk all paths, and they risk being lost even then.<br/>The F&aelig; perceive the Trods as similarly coloured, but they do not perceive animal spirits (usually &mdash; more than a few Trods align along drover routes and horse-paths), still Trodding is often represented as an Ordeal (The Suggested Ordeal from the Card may provide inspiration).<br/>Lea and Trods are expressions of Psychosocial Action Spaces that overlay the normal Action Space. And these Heroes travel "supernaturally" through the Psychosocial Space not the real world. These lines are typically given colours and Difficulties that must be matched with cards to travel along them (see Psychosocial Action Spaces for more details).'),
        array(
        'Ability' => 'Shapeshifting',
        'Description'=>'Mostly accessible to Bulmäs who walk Lea Paths, but proven to be a separate, but allied ability. Shapeshifting is as much the gift that allows the Bulmäs to walk certain paths with such assuredness, as it is a result of Lea walking. Bulmäs rarely disentangle the two unless they walk the Broccen lifestyle, which involves walking the Lea without leaving your territory. A few others have Shapeshifting abilities although these are often very limited.',
        'Rules' => 'Lea cards are played and remain in place on a character, where they add their Pips to all Scores the Bulmäs generates that reflects this animal form. Many Shapeshifters will have a Significator card that represents their preferrred shape. Some may have a limited number of shapes that they can achieve requiring a Proficiency in the shape (which is what limits Bulmäs) or a Lorical Destiny that provides a limited set of cards. Others may achieve the shape of any Lea card played. It should be noted that cosmetic shapeshifting is typically just a roll to beat the Difficulty of the Shapeshift.'),
        array(
        'Ability' => 'Prescience',
        'Description'=>'Knowledge of the future allows Heroes to change the time-line. Some Heroes have senses that allow them to avoid danger, or even anticipate the most unlikely scenarios, and plan accordingly.',
        'Rules' => 'Prescience is usually best represented by Heroes having the ability to Reload. The Hero can Save almost whenever they like, and then can Reload back to that Save when they can afford it. This allows them to "scout" ahead and then Reload with all that knowledge intact.'),
        array(
        'Ability' => 'Metamagic',
        'Description'=>'Metamagic is the ability to alter the rules of nature, to allow or disallow various magics and technologies. In T13 different Ages and settings will have different technologies and magics, they change over time as the public changes their concepts of normality. Metamagic allows these changes to be forced, at least within a limited area or period.',
        'Rules' => 'If magic is impossible then any magic should cost 101 Chi, the same would apply to any Technology, however technically this is a major Retcon, 66 Chi should be enough for most Retcons such as allowing limited magic. Making something impossible is usually more tricky, but making something impossible (or possible) for a while is usually equal to whatever the Chi cost is for that effect + the Extend Duration (and perhaps a Location Size although that is not always necessary).'),
        array(
        'Ability' => 'Quantum Sliding',
        'Description'=>'Some Heroes seem to have an ability to choose how random events unfold. They perform this not by altering probabilities with magic, but instead by shifting themselves partially into the closest quantum wave-collapse universe where the result they want is happening. In extreme cases the Hero may "vanish" from their original universe, through Quantum Immotality.',
        'Rules' => 'Most often this acts as Chi Boosting, but minor retcons and changes are possible, until the Character slips into a universe too far removed from the original.'),
        array(
        'Ability' => 'Access Alternate Memories',
        'Description'=>'Paradox Warriors, Mercari and many other Heroes are capable of remembering things from their other lives. Sometimes they may remember a Past-Life, or may access a memory from the entity that lives in their cerebellum, or they may see a flash of their life in another universe. Accessing Alternate Memories is usually done while dreaming and lasts until the next time you lose consciousness. This sort of swapping can occur randomly whenever a Hero Gains enough Chi if they are not in control of their abilities yet.',
        'Rules' => 'Accessing Alternate Memories actually means that for 1 Chi a Hero may swap a Proficiency from one Alternate to another. Annexes can also be swapped between Alternates if required; Skills can be swapped for 3 Chi, Talents for 5 Chi and Powers for 7 Chi. If swapping a Proficiency could create a new Skill, Talent or Power, then the appropriate cost as though they were being swapped is used.'),
        array(
        'Ability' => 'Lorical Destiny',
        'Description'=>'Sometimes a Hero is only a Hero because a prophecy made them the Chosen One, such Heroes are not in charge of their own fate, they are guided by other forces in the universe. While they may have incredible abilities these abilities will seemingly only work in service of the prophecy that created them.',
        'Rules' => 'A Hero with a Lorical Destiny can replace any card in their Hand with one from the Lore Spread that created their Lore. Additionally, even if they have no Hand currently, they may play Ordeal Cards that match cards from the Lore spread as Wyrd Tarot, Lea or even as Yarn cards (Yarn should only be possible if the Prophecy may be in doubt- and it should be Narrated by the Referee or the Yarn-Teller who created the Prophecy).'),
        array(
        'Ability' => 'Boost Scale',
        'Description'=>'Some Heroes are just better than other people. Everything about them is beyond what a normal person is capable of. These Heroes are just stronger, tougher and smarter. This ability is most obvious in heroes with supernatural or divine blood',
        'Rules' => 'Heroes may give up 1 Card from their Hand to increase their Scale by 1 even beyond their number of Hitches. They may do this as many times as they have Cards in their Hand, until they have no Hand left. The Hand Cards may be regained if the Character purchases Scale normally (and they are still below the number of Hitches). Scale can also be lowered by Twists which may release the Card again.'),
        array(
        'Ability' => 'Million-To-One-Shot',
        'Description'=>'All Heroes can stand in the face of complete disaster and some how achieve that one in a million chance that no one expected. Sometimes this victory seems to cost the Hero almost everything.',
        'Rules' => 'When a Hero Character is faced with no other choice they can spend all their current Chi at once. This Chi is converted into Yarn when it is spent however the Referee will narrate the result of the Yarn spent. Note that Million-To-One-Shots can have a profound and dramatic affect on the setting and can even shift genre or era.'),
        array(
        'Ability' => '',
        'Description'=>'',
        'Rules' => ''),
    ); 
    public static $heroTypes =array(
        //Faery-Commoners, Changelings, Eelafin, Mercari, Wyrdchilde, Human-reincarnated Bulmäs, and Paradox Warriors
        /* array(
        'Hero_Type' => 'Bulmäs (Shapeshifter)',
        'Description'=>'Bulmäs souls incarnated in mortal bodies (typically by consumption of a Soul-Fruit) can often become confused or lost, with the powerful Bulmäs soul that has centuries of memories finding the mortal soul with only a few months or decades of memories almost too subtle and flimsy to recognise as a soul. Only the most careful of Bulmäs, such as All-Walkers can manage to incarnate in a human without something going wrong. Even when the Bulmäs does not consume the resident soul, even the original personality may be overwhelmed by the memories unless the Bulmäs knows how to read or tie a soul without eating it. ',
        'Rules' => 'Bulmäs Characters can use their Hand of Cards to access the Lea in a number of ways, although they can be limited by the Path or nature of their incarnation. Human-incarnated Bulmäs are usually limited, but inventive in how they can use the Lea and these cards without training. Most commonly they will access the shapeshifting abilities, although they may be initially blind to what paths are available or only access their Significator path. See Bulmas Character Rules.'),
        array(
        'Hero_Type' => 'Cleric',
        'Description'=>'Depending upon who you ask Clerics either directly channel the divine power of their God or Pantheon, or they are just a deluded Mercari. For the sake of flavour let&apos;s assume that they are&apos; just Mercari. A Cleric can access abilities through the power of prayer that are comparable to other Hero types although they perceive this ability as external to themselves in some way.',
        'Rules' => 'Clerics may gain access to a Hand of cards, but they rarely play them without praying first. They may spend Chi on Actions when they believe they are being protected or empowered by their god. Typically they will Save when they pray to their god several times a day, and may Reload, but experience the original memory as a religiously encoded vision, voice of warning or guardian angel.'),
        array(
        'Hero_Type' => 'Chosen One',
        'Description'=>'Chosen Ones are beings gifted incredible powers (often by a Lore) so that they can fulfil some ancient prophecy. Chosen Ones are often anticipated by religions, or more often small cults, and their abilities can seem divinely insprired, but they typically are not.',
        'Rules' => 'Chosen Ones typically can spend Chi to affect their Roles and to Doom Weave, but typically they do not gain access to a Hand of Wyrd Tarot. Their Doom-Weaving is purely based on Chi expended to create the desired result. Chosen Ones are often limited in Doom-Weaving to only the cards in the Revelation/Lore Spread that created them. Chosen Ones can also sometimes use Yarn Card effects from the same spread, and even Bulmäs abilities are occasionally possible.'),
        array(
        'Hero_Type' => 'Demigod',
        'Description'=>'Demigods are hybrids between mortals and divine beings (usually the more powerful ones that call themselves gods). Typically such demigods are stronger and more powerful than mortals, and often have some magical ability that is tied to their divine ancestor&apos;s godhead, these powers often expand or explore one aspect of their parents sphere or domain, their parent should always be able to perform any feat that their child performs, although perhaps with differing levels of success.',
        'Rules' => 'The abilities of Demigods vary wildly, not just from god to god, but from pantheon to pantheon, and depending upon exactly how mortal the other parent was. Some are born giants with Size Annexes, others are simply born with a Base Scale that is increased, typically at least +5 over normal. Demigods that have some claim to prescience or fate manipulation will have access to Wyrd Tarot Hands, typically having +1 card in their Hand. Demigods may learn to use Chi for almost any purpose, especially if taught or gifted magic by their Divine ancestor, but most invest their Chi in Prizes.'),
        array(
        'Hero_Type' => 'Eelafin (Changeling)',
        'Description'=>'Hybrids of F&aelig; and mortals, occasionally with a smattering of Bulmäs in the mix, Changelings are usually a direct merging of their two parents. If their mother is human and father is a Sidhe Noble then you would expect a child that combined the almost crystaline features of the Sidhe with the aspect of a normal human. Such a child might be giften in magic, and even perhaps be able to read and weave Dooms. The Eelafin are a special case as their tribes included full-bloods who forgot they were F&aelig; when the gates closed, and their magic died. Only vestigial magicks allowed those of F&aelig; Blood to find each other while they lived and died as mortals. When the gates reopened, or perhaps once they had approached some other gates, the Eelafin were revealed as a new expression of F&aelig;ry blood and magic.',
        'Rules' => 'Changelings typically have a Wyrd Tarot hand and may have other forms of magic, such as illusions, flight, dream-walking, shapeshifting (typically between a few forms) or trodding (F&aelig;ry Lea Walking). Changelings typically resemble their F&aelig;ry parent, while Eelafin resemble other members of their tribe, it is hard to spot what F&aelig; formed which bloodline, except for the Royalle who aknowledge their Sidhe and Sith ancestors.'),
        array(
        'Hero_Type' => 'Faery-Commoner',
        'Description'=>'',
        'Rules' => ''),
        array(
        'Hero_Type' => 'Gestalt',
        'Description'=>'',
        'Rules' => ''),
        array(
        'Hero_Type' => 'Magus',
        'Description'=>'',
        'Rules' => ''),
        array(
        'Hero_Type' => 'Mercari',
        'Description'=>'',
